Higgs boson explored
The announcement of the probable discovery of the Higgs boson caused a justifiable stir last summer.
There is an opinion that this boson is involved in the mechanism that is responsible for all the matter in the universe.
And then there is the last particle whose existence is predicted by the standard model - our best or &quot;least bad&quot; explanation of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has not yet been observed empirically.
However, physicists are still not 100% certain that it is the Higgs boson.
There is no doubt that we have a brand new particle that closely resembles the Higgs boson as predicted by the Standard Model.
New data released this week during a major physics congress in Kyoto seem to confirm it, but we still need all the data to be absolutely sure.
However, let&#39;s assume it&#39;s a Higgs boson, since the risks of error seem small, and see what it&#39;s really about.
In this world there is an absolutely indisputable law that no two things can occur at the same time in the same place.
There&#39;s no way around this rule - and don&#39;t try too hard or you&#39;ll hurt yourself.
Although particle physics is a very strange world, it turns out that there is a similar law: the Pauli exclusion principle, according to which no two particles can occupy the same space at the same time if they are in the same &quot;quantum state&quot; - this &quot;state&quot; roughly speaking creates some of their properties.
Physicists further divide particles into two categories.
On the one hand, we find ordered citizens, or fermions, which obediently obey the Pauli principle.
And at the other end are the bosons, vile anarchists who value nothing at all - certainly not this principle, which means that they can easily be in the same place at the same time.
These bosons are further divided into two groups according to the (absolutely awesome, by the way) facility that is The Particle Adventure at Berkeley Labs: mesons, which we&#39;ll ignore here, and &quot;force particles,&quot; which propagate the great forces of nature and which are the Higgs boson probably related in some way.
However, it must be said that these bosons are not as exotic animals as one might think.
If you&#39;re reading this article, it&#39;s because of a boson of unusual banality: the photon, or &quot;particle of light,&quot; which is the &quot;carrier&quot; of the electromagnetic force.
When a particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes its direction, it &quot;disrupts&quot; the electromagnetic field in that particular place, similar to a pebble thrown into a pond.
From this &quot;disturbance&quot; an electromagnetic wave (light, infrared or ultraviolet radiation, etc.) will arise, and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the bosons, the &quot;carriers of force&quot;.
A more stable field
It is the same with the Higgs boson, with the only difference that another field, the Higgs field, must be &quot;disrupted&quot; in order for this boson to appear.
This Higgs field is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to excite it, it is necessary to reach very high energy values, similar to the frozen surface of a pond, which only a very large boulder will clear.
For this reason, it is necessary to use such a huge accelerator part as the accelerator in the CERN laboratory - the Large Hadron Collider with welcoming beams is a circle with a circumference of 27 km! - to be able to develop such energy.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is useful again to clarify the relationship between the Higgs and matter.
Neither all particles nor all materials react with the electromagnetic field.
Some, like magnets, do, but others don&#39;t - a piece of paper, for example, will never stick on the fridge by itself.
And anyway, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do have some mass, while others (such as a photon, let&#39;s look at it) do not.
And Ms. Nováková asks what all these researches are for, what will they &quot;bring us&quot;?
From a science perspective, this is a confirmation of the validity of the Standard Model (SM), allowing physicists to scrutinize any discrepancies between observations and SM predictions.
In addition, quite a few physicists literally wish to find them, because the slightest difference could open up the space of &quot;new physics&quot; and close some gaps in the model.
It should be noted that the model still has huge flaws, it does not provide any clarification of gravity (whoah!) or dark matter, which makes up approximately 80% of the cosmic mass (again whoah!).
However, the CERN facility has so far not discovered such contradictions.
Responses
The responses of these researches in the daily life of Mr. and Mrs. Novák can only be predicted with great difficulty, but it would be a mistake to assume that there will be none.
Behold: in the very early 1960s, the laser pioneers at Bell Labs had no idea of the revolution their work would spark.
They envisioned a scientific use, but nothing more.
Physicist Willard Boyle - who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who created the first steady laser beam (the previous beams were pulsed) in 1962, I&#39;ve already said - the laser was initially considered as such a &quot;lab toy &quot;.
