With Bitcoin you can pay and sell without banks
All negatives of current financial transactions based on central banks, identified transactions and processing costs between beneficiaries.
Moreover, as is often true within these technologies, there is an obvious political outlook: the belief that the current financial system built on banking monopolies leads to financial crises.
Bitcoin, whose inventor is Satoshi Nakamoto (pseudonym), represents both virtual money (convertible, however, to dollars, euros...) and a secure transfer protocol similar to BitTorrent, which enables the exchange of files between pairs of partners.
Thanks to the 15,000 computers connected to the network, approximately 200,000 transactions have already been registered.
About a thousand websites already accept bitcoins as gifts or as a means of payment.
The bitcoin exchange rate first reached a maximum of 30 dollars (23 euros) in June 2011, five months later it fell to 2 dollars, today it hovers around 10 dollars (an overview of the exchange rates is given on the bitcoincharts.com page).
Compared to the world&#39;s exchange for real money or financial products, this is nothing impressive.
And yet the European Central Bank (ECB) is interested in this fact in its report on virtual finance, which was published in October.
He describes Bitcoin as &quot;the most successful virtual money&quot;, &quot;competing with the dollar and the euro&quot; and &quot;similar to ordinary money&quot;.
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual money in that it is like &quot;credits&quot; used to progress in a video game that one earns by playing or that one can buy (and sometimes trade back).
The social network Facebook has also developed a similar system.
Every month, however, the central authority checks and processes individual communications.
In the case of Bitcoin, all nodes of the network are custodians of the current account book, controllers, issuers of money, and both buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually between two electronic addresses using email.
However, the user can choose a different address for each payment, thus ensuring anonymity.
The file of information related to this transaction is electronically signed with a double-key encryption system.
The network can thus verify the legitimacy of the transaction.
The contents of the file also make it possible to ensure that the exchanged bitcoins exist in a public ledger that is distributed throughout the network.
The key stage is to write this new transaction in this ledger.
It takes place by solving a mathematical problem given to computers, the solver of which, a kind of temporary central banker, will have the right to write this additional line.
This is the file cutting phase; i.e. about transforming a huge file into a shorter and unique digital footprint.
Computers will &quot;take over&quot; this new transaction and add a number to it, only then &quot;chop&quot; the whole.
The goal is to find a number that gives a specific fingerprint (lots of leading zeros).
Once this number is found, other nodes can easily check its correctness.
The transaction then appears indestructibly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification would alter the print.
If the user wanted to fraudulently pay twice with the same money very quickly (within ten minutes), the network will confirm only one of the two transactions - the other will be abandoned, since each of them has a different fingerprint.
The computer that solves the challenge wins 50 Bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, this reward is divided by two regularly, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is thus limited to 21 million, but they can be divided up to hundred millionths, so there is room for margin...
The difficulty of the given task also increases with the increasing level of calculation.
The network has had its ups and downs.
Websites that provide services for Bitcoin have been hacked and stored Bitcoins have been stolen.
&quot;The exploited loophole is not related to the protocol itself,&quot; assures Pierre Noizat, who founded Paymium, a real-money payment company that uses the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also checks money laundering possibilities thanks to this anonymous service.
But this problem also applies to cash.
Major players like Wikipedia reject donations of this nature.
Others, like the WordPress blogging platform, accept them.
Adi Shamir and Dorit Ron of the Weizmann Institute in Israel recently analyzed the ledger of current accounts and showed that almost 80% of bitcoins are not in circulation.
&quot;Huge discounts&quot; were launched in November.
&quot;Thirty thousand dollars were exchanged,&quot; exults Jon Holmquist, who works for Coinabul, a bitcoin-to-gold exchange.
Pierre Noizat, who is also the author of an educational book about this money, has great faith in the potential of this technology as a transaction network.
His system, Paytunia, is equivalent to a credit card (with real money) or contactless mobile payment, but uses the Bitcoin system to verify transactions, which makes it cheaper.
In addition, the wearer manages his identity and can thus remain anonymous.
The system is easy to set up at dealers, where there is no need to install new terminals or software.
It is enough to tell the address, which can be &quot;photographed and recognized&quot; with the phone, explains Pierre Noizat, who assures that he already has thousands of users.
There is a general movement towards challenging hierarchical systems and moving towards more horizontal systems.
&quot;It will take some time for Bitcoin to take hold, but 2013 could be a decisive year,&quot; he predicts.
In addition, the ECB in its report foresees a reassessment of the various risks that are considered to be elevated today if this kind of money is successful.
