Difficult work on the Egyptian constitution
President Muhammad Morsi has started another game of poker.
As Egypt remains the most divided in its history over the promulgation of a constitution that temporarily grants it unlimited powers, it has decided to play vabank.
On Wednesday, he announced, regardless of everyone else&#39;s opinion, that the Constituent Assembly would approve the final text tomorrow.
Less than a week ago, the head of state granted this assembly another two months to complete the necessary work.
For almost two years, Egypt has been using a provisional text that has been amended many times, weakening the country&#39;s constitutional stability and leading to legal disputes.
This new initiative only further strengthened the country&#39;s divisiveness.
From the point of view of the opposition, the president persists in his &quot;autocratic delirium&quot;, continues to &quot;break his word&quot; and &quot;tramp on the law&quot;.
However, his supporters assure that it is a means to turn around the constitutional and political crisis as quickly as possible and speed up the transition process.
A referendum should be held in two weeks.
It is a very short period of time that will force the Brotherhood to withdraw from the intention of clarifying the text to the Egyptians article by article.
It is also a way for the president to regain national and democratic legitimacy as protests sweep the country.
As he confirmed in an interview with the American weekly Time, Muhammad Morsi seems convinced that Egyptians will vote in favor.
Especially since this hastily organized vote presents the Egyptian people with an ultimatum: &quot;Either approve my text or I will retain unlimited powers&quot;, which should otherwise end after the new constitution is approved.
And in this special atmosphere yesterday, 85 deputies of the mentioned constitutional assembly with a large majority of Islamists approved the text.
Most Liberals were absent from the vote.
In mid-November, not long before the promulgation of the constitution, they slammed the door saying that they had no opportunity to assert their views.
Defenders of human rights, civil society or members of religious minorities imitated their step.
In order to achieve a quorum, 11 substitutes were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some of them are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
It is not surprising then that the articles of the constitution were often voted unanimously.
Commentators further noted that one of the few controversies that day revolved around... the clock for prayer, when some committee members opined that the meeting room clocks were not adjusted properly.
The text, which was voted on yesterday evening, consists of 234 articles.
The subject of general attention, Article 2, ultimately remains the same as the 1971 version of the constitution and states that &quot;the principles of Sharia law are the main source of law&quot;.
The Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the fundamental demands, hoped to replace the term &quot;principles&quot; with the term &quot;rules&quot;, which would allow stricter application.
For the Islamists, the fact that this article has not been corrected is a sign of their goodwill and respect towards other parts of Egyptian society.
&quot;Hypocrisy,&quot; object the liberals, who see in it only a rhetorical problem.
According to them, the Islamization of the constitution takes place through other articles.
They focus in particular on Article 220, which entrusts al-Azhar University with an advisory role, especially for issues of checking the conformity of laws with Sharia law.
According to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, this is disturbing because &quot;the people called to speak are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy.
One can see in it the beginnings of a theocracy&quot;.
The fact that the next chancellor of the university should be less moderate than the current one is fueling the liberals&#39; fears even more.
&quot;So far, there has been no concrete religious consequence.
With this constitution, Egypt remains a largely civil state.
Most of the lawyers who worked on this text are not ulama, but university workers, many of them studied in French schools,&quot; mitigates the concerns of Alexis Blouet, who is preparing a work on the constitutional transition in Egypt.
However, he agrees that &quot;there may be contradictions regarding the interpretation of Article 220, because the terms used in it belong to the religious vocabulary.
There is a particular reference to &quot;fiqh&quot; [Islamic jurisprudence, note ed.].
And in the future, the question may arise as to what extent civil judges are competent to comment on this&quot;.
In addition to the religious aspects, the text approved yesterday is highly criticized because of the expanded powers it grants to the president of the republic.
The Muslim Brotherhood insists that they have been significantly curtailed compared to the former regime.
Another point of contention: the powers vested in the military.
In accordance with the wishes of the army representatives, the verification of the defense budget will not be carried out by the Parliament, but by the National Defense Council.
Furthermore, trials involving civilians will not be prohibited in military courts, as requested by associations for the protection of human rights.
These associations talk about their doubts regarding the text, which they say is directed against freedom.
The criminal offense of blasphemy is retained and insult continues to be prohibited, which could have serious consequences for freedom of expression, especially for the press.
In addition, no article deals with the protection of women, emphasizes Heba Morayefová from the Human Rights Watch organization.
According to her, the only positive point is the prohibition of torture mentioned in Article 36.
This word was not mentioned in the previous constitution.
While the Egyptian president was scheduled to make a televised speech last night, demonstrations are planned for this afternoon.
The supporters of the head of state will demonstrate on Saturday.
Holy places, the navel of the world and a sea of saturated salt solution await Ukrainian tourists in Israel
The Promised Land combines the greatness of biblical truths, modern comfort and untouched nature.
AaF has identified the top five reasons why you should visit Israel.
Pay homage to holy places
Visit the Jordan River where Jesus was baptized.
It is claimed that God&#39;s mercy will descend upon all who enter this &quot;spa&quot;.
And Galilee - the place of Jesus&#39; miracles: turning water into wine at the wedding, walking on water, calming the storm and filling the nets.
This is also where Jesus appeared to his disciples and after the resurrection.
But the most holy places are in Jerusalem.
Here, believers will walk the Way of Pain, or Jesus&#39; Way of the Cross (Via Dolorosa in Latin).
It starts at the Fort Antonia - Pretoria - where the trial was held, passes through the streets of the Old Town and leads to the Church of the Holy Sepulcher on Mount Golgotha - to the place of crucifixion, to the stone of anointing and the place where Jesus was buried.
Here is the symbolic Christian navel of the world, which symbolizes the salvation of mankind.
And the Monastery of the Holy Cross in Jerusalem was built on the site where, according to Christian legend, grew the tree from which they made the cross for Jesus&#39; crucifixion.
Jerusalem is also home to the holiest site for Jews - the Wailing Wall, the remnant of the Temple that was destroyed by the Romans in 70 AD
According to tradition, people of different faiths leave notes with wishes here, which are then filled out.
Take a vertical journey
The ruins of the Masada fortress remain from the secret shelter from the enemy that Herod the Great built in 25 BC for his family.
The ruins are located on cliffs in the mountains at an altitude of 450 m above sea level.
Only those who engage in mountain climbing can reach it by their own efforts.
The others will be taken to this historic mountain by cable car.
And in the north of the country, at an altitude of 1600-2040 m, there is the famous Hermon ski resort, which experiences a huge influx of tourists in the winter months.
A shuttle bus transports tourists to this ski paradise from the bottom of the hill.
The total length of the mountain slopes is 45 km.
According to an ancient legend, pagan gods supposedly lived on top of the mountain.
Visit unique museums
There are around 300 museums in this country.
You cannot visit them all in one trip.
But at least five of them, the most interesting ones, are definitely worth a visit.
Among them is the Israel Museum, located near the Knesset (Parliament).
It houses the ancient Qumran manuscripts, or the Dead Sea Scrolls, which were found in the caves of the Judean Desert, as well as approximately 500,000 archaeological and anthropological exhibits.
The Art Museum in Tel-Aviv is also worth a visit.
Impressionists and expressionists Monet, Pissarro, Renoir, Cézanne, Sisley, Matisse, Modigliani, Chagall, Picasso are widely represented in his exhibition.
In Acre, you can visit the Al Basha Spa Museum, which presents visitors with several rooms of an ancient Turkish bath with mannequins of spa users and spa attendants from that time.
In Caesarea, the unique private Ralli museum is worth a visit, where you can admire the sculptures of Dalí and Rodin.
There are no tour guides or gift shops.
Admission is free and donations are strictly refused.
The fifth museum - the Holocaust Museum or Yad Vashem in Tel Aviv - tells about one of the most dramatic pages of history.
The most tragic part of the museum - the Children&#39;s Memorial - was built in memory of 1.5 million children who were murdered in concentration camps and gas chambers.
You step inside - and find yourself in total darkness.
The stars are twinkling.
And there are the names of Jewish children and the names of the countries in which they perished.
Ukraine is also mentioned.
Improve your health
The three main spa centers of Israel are located on the coast of the Mediterranean, Red and Dead seas.
Each of them offers swimming pools, water parks, dolphinariums and oceanariums.
It is interesting that you can swim in the Red Sea even in the winter months, because the water temperature does not fall below 21 degrees Celsius and the air warms up to 23 degrees.
The Dead Sea is even warmer, and people swim in it all year round.
By the way, the Dead Sea is the most special sea in the world, it is located at the lowest land point on the planet - at a level of 417 m below sea level.
The azure water in it is a saturated salt solution that easily keeps even non-swimmers afloat.
The surrounding landscape is unrealistically beautiful.
Head here to undergo treatment using salt water - brine, and medicinal mud that can treat health problems such as dermatitis, allergies, asthma, eczema, arthritis, bronchitis, diabetes, to heal your frayed nerves.
Touch the mysterious ancient past
It is protected by the ancient part of Tel Aviv - the town of Jaffa on the coast of the Mediterranean Sea.
A famous sea route connecting Egypt, Syria, Anatolia and Mesopotamia passed through them.
Mentions of this city are found in the oldest Greek and Egyptian legends.
According to legend, this is the place where Noah built his ark and Perseus saved the beautiful Andromeda, with whom they lived a long and happy life together.
Tourists really love wandering through the narrow streets, named after the signs of the zodiac.
It is said that if you press yourself against the walls in the alley of &quot;your&quot; sign, luck will favor you.
In Jaffa, you may meet newlyweds who come from all over Israel and even from other countries to have their photos taken.
And in Caesarea - the city of King Herod - you can walk through the Roman theater and &quot;conquer&quot; the fortress of the Crusaders.
In Roman times, Caesarea was the capital of Judea and the seat of the Roman procurators, including Pontius Pilate.
The carefully restored theater is now used for evening concerts and opera performances.
Tourists, for a word
If you are going to Israel, you don&#39;t need to worry about your imperfect English: about 30% of the population in this country speak Russian.
On the trip, it is better to take money with you not in euros, but in dollars, which you can easily exchange for shekels (now 1 dollar is about 3.8 shekels).
Urban transport is mainly buses, but there is a high-speed tram in Jerusalem, and the city of Haifa has the only metro line in the country with six stations that connects the lower city with the upper city.
Basically, it is an underground cable car.
Traveling by all types of city public transport costs 6 shekels, for which you can travel for 1.5 hours with transfers.
In Israel, according to Jewish tradition, Shabbat is celebrated on Saturday.
From Friday evening until sunset on Saturday, markets, shops and public transport stop working.
And on Sunday morning the work week begins.
In many cafes, restaurants and hotels, you only get kosher food: with the exception of pork, seafood, fish without scales and dishes that contain a combination of milk and meat.
They offer a large selection of lamb and beef dishes, soups and desserts made from coconut milk, traditional Jewish hummus porridge, various types of sauces, ground chickpea balls - falafel, fruits and vegetables.
There are no stray dogs on the streets of Israeli cities.
On the other hand, there are many fattened cats that gracefully &quot;wander around according to their taste&quot;.
In the evening you can see them sleeping on the roofs of parked cars.
Purring cats love crowded places and will gobble up every treat with gusto.
Renting a car will cost from $37 per day (Hyundai Getz) to $188 per day (Audi A6, Volvo S80) depending on the car brand.
Plus insurance - $15 per day.
And renting a bike will cost around 15 shekels per day.
Museum tickets cost an average of 30 shekels.
Expressed in numbers
In 2012, more than three million tourists from all over the world visited Israel.
Most citizens of the USA, Russia, France, Germany, Italy, England and Ukraine came to get to know the country and rest.
118.8 thousand people visited the Promised Land from January to October 2012. of Ukrainian tourists, which is 51% more than in the same period in 2010, before the abolition of visas on February 9, 2011.
The &quot;Great and Powerful&quot; will announce it to Moscow: emigrants will save money on the language
While parliamentarians and human rights defenders are still debating the law on mandatory language tests, fraudsters selling &quot;fake&quot; certificates have already appeared in the country
13 million foreign workers come to Moscow, St. Petersburg and other Russian cities every year.
Most of them are citizens of Central Asia: Uzbekistan, Tajikistan, Turkmenistan.
Their only goal is to earn enough money to support their families back home.
On December 1, a law entered into force according to which every working migrant will be required to pass a test on the knowledge of the Russian language.
For now, this rule only applies to those who intend to work in the service, housing and community management, lifestyle and retail sectors.
However, the FMS promises that in time the relevant tests will be mandatory for all visitors.
However, the exams will consist not only of language skills, but also of Russian history and the basics of law.
Knowledge of the language will also need to be confirmed in order to obtain and extend a work permit.
The exception applies only to citizens of countries where Russian is the official language.
Even people who successfully managed to achieve certification and obtain an academic diploma before the collapse of the USSR in 1991 are not subject to this law.
Benefit, condemnation and protection of rights
The network of examination sites will work under the auspices of the Pushkin Institute of the Russian Language, the University of Friendship between Nations, Moscow State University, St. Petersburg and other Russian universities.
Migrants can take exams in all cities; already today more than 160 such centers are opened in Russia.
The initiative to support the introduction of testing was also supported by members of the State Duma and FMS (Federal Migration Service).
But before the law entered into force, human rights defenders were able to ask the question many times in the press: what will it actually bring?
What will the obligation to know the language change for Russians and for the visitors themselves?
First of all - the representatives of the migration service answer - it will make it possible to reduce the number of people who suffer as a result of &quot;slave labor.&quot;
Today, many people are talking about protecting the rights of migrant workers, explains Viktor Sebelev, Chairman of the Board of Directors of the FMS of Russia in Tajikistan.
The protection of their rights should begin even before their departure.
Only the system of organized recruitment will make it possible to solve 90% of the problems of foreign workers.
Problems arise with emigrants without a profession, without education, who do not know the language and do not have a medical examination.
Without knowing the language - Sebelev says with conviction - the future migrant is doomed to clashes with dishonest people who, under the pretext of helping him, will provide him with a &quot;voucher&quot; to terrible, cramped hostels, in which he and dozens of others like himself will languish for months without food or documents and toil for 12 to 14 hours a day.
We receive many complaints from our migrant workers.
&quot;They promise them one thing in their homeland, but upon arrival they cheat them, confiscate their passports, do not pay the promised wages,&quot; confirms Tolib Šaripov, head of the Main Tajik Labor Migration Administration of the MS.
Don&#39;t curse!
Even less, many citizens of the Central Asian republics who intend to go to Russia for work admit that they not only do not know the language of the country they want to enter, but they do not even have experience in the work in question.
Of course, it is not so much their fault as it is a misfortune: very few Turkmens, Uzbeks, Tajiks can afford to get at least a reasonable basic education.
After all, their families also need something to feed the children, not to mention the fact that they need to be properly clothed, shod and equipped for school.
As children reach working age, they must go to work at the first opportunity.
Without knowledge of the language it is difficult - they admit.
&quot;You feel humiliated and inferior.&quot;
It is true that with regard to the law on language tests, human rights defenders point to one important thing.
Testing will only be done for those migrants who have legal status.
If they don&#39;t have it, they won&#39;t pass exams or get any other official job.
Meanwhile, the majority of migrant workers continue to live illegally in Russia.
&quot;Welcome, or Uninvited Entry Prohibited&quot;
Many of the incoming workers claim that it is not easy to get official status in our country.
The reason - bureaucratic obstacles and all those language difficulties.
In addition, legalization costs money: from 12 to 16 thousand rubles.
But a fake registration can be obtained quickly and only one and a half thousand.
The employees of the Russian police know that we basically have fake documents, without registration, and from this there are cases of extortion.
&quot;They demand a hundred, two for cigarettes, tea,&quot; - Tajik citizen Umed Khushkadamov shared his experience with journalists.
&quot;Come on, don&#39;t be stingy, buy a painting&quot;
On the first day of the language law&#39;s validity, it was discovered that not only migrants&#39; registration documents are fake.
FMS employees have already seized several fake certificates of completion of the language test.
Counterfeit documents are printed on an ordinary color printer.
Of course, they did not get to the new owners for free: each of the migrants, hoping to ease the problem of passing the tests, paid seven thousand rubles for this document.
This is two and a half times more than taking the official test: it will cost migrant workers three thousand rubles.
The main task of the near future is to secure the system against corruption so that workers cannot simply buy documents, both government officials and human rights defenders agree on this.
For now, government authorities can promise foreign workers who fail the tests the necessary time to complete a course in the basics of the Russian language.
Visitors who do not speak Russian are expected to work in areas that do not require active interaction with people.
