Augmented reality is a popular topic among fans of modern virtual reality technologies; lately it means perceiving the world especially through the prism of special glasses.
At the beginning of the summer at its annual conference, Google demonstrated a working model of this innovation, and in November it was announced that Microsoft had also filed an application for a corresponding patent.
From an interview with the head of the group of interactive 3D technologies at Microsoft&#39;s Cambridge laboratory, Šaram Izadi, it follows that for scientists of this company, glasses are already a thing of the past.
They are attracted by the prospect of manipulating virtual objects in the air with their bare hands, creating virtual public spaces.
- Please tell us roughly what your research group does?
- We deal with human-machine interactions, but at the same time we try to push the boundaries of this interaction.
So far, humanity is stuck at the stage of working with pixels on a flat screen, at most sometimes touching the screen with a finger.
We want to look 5-10 years ahead and anticipate significant changes in this interaction.
For example, the Xbox console and Kinect sensors - this is a step forward, and today almost no Xbox is on sale without Kinect sensors, because the possibility of controlling with gestures is very interesting for everyone.
- What else awaits us in the future?
- Although the Kinect system has brought interaction to a physical level, a great many interactions still take place on a flat screen, sometimes in 3D.
The input flow of information has improved (the system accepts more data), but the output flow has not yet improved.
We are trying to change this, we are working on truly three-dimensional display systems based on various technologies, including projective ones.
It is necessary to let the computer world into our physical world, to make it more real.
For this purpose, however, it is necessary to know not only the user, but also the space around him.
Then we will be able to add virtual objects to the real world in a much more suitable form.
And first of all - to hell with those stupid virtual reality helmets!
- What do you think about voice control?
This is a popular thing, but isn&#39;t it overrated?
- Of course, it cannot be considered a panacea - the question of privacy arises, because we do not always want to inform others around us about our activities and intentions.
In fact, all types of interaction with computers are good, but in their own environment.
For example, for controlling devices in public places, we had a project in which we thought about gestures, but not sweeping ones, just such stingy, short ones.
At the same time, gestures would not be captured by the camera of the device, but by a bracelet that would monitor the movements of bones and muscles.
It&#39;s big so far, but in theory it can be shrunk down to the size of a wristwatch.
However, in general, the future has a mixed type of control, for example, gesture + voice.
- And how?
- For example, how do you ask me to give you this can of lemonade?
You say it and show it at the same time.
- I usually just talk.
- Oh, that will be very difficult to recognize.
- So you want to make the user adapt to what the machine can or can&#39;t do at that moment?
- This is not necessary at all, but it is a mutual rapprochement.
I think that in the near future we will have to work primarily on the development of new types of sensors that can detect human reactions more accurately.
These can be, for example, laser sensors that provide relatively good depth resolution, this is very important.
- Speaking of your work with Xbox Kinect sensors, what are your requirements for modern cameras?
Not enough resolution, depth or something else today?
- Basically the current generation - that&#39;s what we can bounce off of in our 3D recognition work.
Of course, it would be good to get 8 megapixels at 1000 f/s.
But it&#39;s not just about the megapixels themselves, but like the matrix and depth.
Looking at it now, all the current technologies are insufficient for us - this gives the algorithm designers work.
So we have to keep in mind not only the resolution in the X and Y axes, but also the Z.
So the speed, the number of frames per second, is also very important.
Human movement is quite dynamic and current 30 frames per second streams are frankly a bit low, especially for gestures.
Stephen Betishes from our lab in Redmond made a touch sensor with an adjustable processing delay of 1 to 100ms, while current, mass-produced sensors are closer to the latter value (60-100ms).
Not everyone understands the extent to which this affects human-machine interaction.
For me, the equivalent of such a device would be very useful at work, I just don&#39;t need so many touches, but I need some extra frames per second.
- And increasing the number of cameras is not necessary?
- The Kinect system now uses three &quot;cameras&quot;, one of which is actually an infrared transmitter and the other a receiver of the reflected signal.
And the third camera - it&#39;s actually a regular visible range sensor.
This is not used to determine the depth of the object.
More cameras could potentially solve the problem...
Or make it worse, because it would increase the necessary volume of performed calculations.
It would be nice to make a flexible analog Kinect system, play around with the curvature of the camera placement and see how that helps with 3D positioning.
- If I remember correctly, Microsoft (unlike Google) did not publicly present its glasses.
Don&#39;t you think that this is one of the most promising platforms when it comes to everyday use of augmented reality technology with special glasses?
- Of course, walking and constantly holding a smartphone in raised hands is not very comfortable, but I think: the strongest option would be a &quot;portable&quot; form of augmented reality, where it would be possible to switch from glasses to a smartphone, projection display and more at any time based on the cloud platform all the way round.
Glasses - this is a very personal device, this is their strength (only you can see private things), and at the same time also a weakness - augmented reality based on glasses does not allow you to work on virtual objects at the same time as other people.
- Imagine for a moment that the manipulation of virtual holographic objects in the air is available not only to Tony Stark in &quot;Iron Man&quot;, but also to an ordinary mortal.
There is one problem that critics often point to: there is no touch response!
Hands don&#39;t feel anything!
What responses is your group preparing to this challenge?
- In my lectures, I often say that augmented reality is the seventh consecutive breakthrough in human-machine interaction.
I think the addition of tactile sensations could easily become the eighth breakthrough.
So far, one of the interesting tricks is being used - using the second hand as a kind of background for imaging.
It records compressions in an excellent way!
But there are also technologies that are really aimed at adding tactility to these &quot;images in the air&quot; - for example, the interference of several directional ultrasound beams at a defined point where the finger is located creates a tactile sensation, but it is still very weak - like blowing on a the bellies of the fingers.
There is also a wrist bracelet that affects the nerve endings in the fingers - also a promising direction.
- Have you ever tried to trick your brain?
For him to think he feels what he seems to feel at that moment when he sees something?
- That&#39;s a good idea, we haven&#39;t tried that yet.
Here comes another challenge that will be fought for a long time - how to make a person who is physically in a very confined space believe that he is walking in an open, practically endless space - we are also working on the concept of running tracks (not at all, like in clubs), moving platforms and also huge balls.
If tricking the brain becomes the goal, then the work is still many years away.
This is what makes working on virtual reality so attractive to researchers - many things are in their infancy.
