The head of the SAO: The control of the black system failed because of the politicians
The Czech Republic has good inspectors and high-quality legislation in connection with public contracts, but it falters in its application.
In an interview with Aktuálně.cz, Vice President of the Supreme Audit Office Miloslav Kala says so.
&quot;The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct - that&#39;s what I think we lack,&quot; Kala comments on the current situation.
Similar conclusions are also indicated by the joint inspection of the Czech and German inspectors.
As an example of incorrect practice, he cites Petr Nečas&#39;s approach to the so-called &quot;black system&quot;.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that ODS will not bother entrepreneurs with its checks - is it banned or allowed?
&quot;The law must be set somehow, and if it prohibits something, then even the prime minister cannot prevent the activity of the office, which has the duty to check and enforce obligations,&quot; states Kala.
At the meeting of the control committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke about a joint project between the Czech and German sides, in which the legislation related to public procurement in both countries was compared.
What exactly was it about?
This is a parallel inspection that we started about two years ago.
To put it simply, the point is that European legislation regulates how public contracts should be handled, followed by individual national legislations and then also by practice itself.
We have put all this together, and even though the inspection is not yet finished, very interesting differences have become apparent to us - generally speaking, the legislation is perhaps &quot;stricter and more perfect&quot; in our country, however, the practice itself is better in some parameters in Germany.
Thus, it is confirmed that it is not enough to create more and more precise rules, but it is necessary to focus on the application of the law itself.
What can this project actually help you with, what will come of it for you?
It is this kind of joint control that could help us to stop making efforts to make the laws more precise, reduce and improve the limits, when it does not have such a positive effect.
Economy means obtaining the appropriate item at a reasonable (but not always the lowest) price, in order to exclude enrichment and possibly criminal behavior.
But by lowering the order limit, we don&#39;t necessarily achieve that.
Perhaps the system will be overwhelmed with so much &quot;paper&quot; that those who want to look for holes in the system will draw from it much more easily than if the limit remained higher.
You are talking about domestic problems with the implementation of public procurement legislation.
How does the inspection system work in Germany?
Is there an office similar to our SAO, or is it set up differently?
As far as the authorities are concerned, the Bundesrechnungshof operates there like the SAO, which is organized similarly to us, it also has a collegium, only it is formed in a slightly different way, but in principle both authorities proceed in a similar way.
The powers are also similar to a certain extent, but because Germany has a federal structure, it also has these accounting courts at the level of the individual federal states - that&#39;s where the system differs from ours.
BRH can only control federal money, in our case represented by state funds.
Public funds, which are managed by regions and municipalities in our country, are checked there at the level of federal accounting courts.
As for the legislation there, is it simpler than ours?
In general, I would not like to compare it without specific data, however, in some respects Germany is referred to as a model, but it cannot be said for sure that it is better in everything.
So is it because they have better controllers?
Certainly not, but I say again, I don&#39;t like such comparisons.
But it must be said that even the countries that we consider to be role models are facing a whole range of problems.
Otherwise, there would be no benefit for them to cooperate with our office, right?
With regard to domestic legislation, what did the amendment to the Public Procurement Act mean for your office, are its effects already being felt somehow?
Given that the period of validity of this amendment is relatively short, it has not yet been reflected in our control actions.
Since we do ex post checks, a certain delay must be expected.
We observe this so far only in the process of preparing future controls - we launched our new tool &quot;detection of risks of wastefulness&quot;, through which we ran through almost 14 thousand public contracts, and analyzed them - there, of course, the changes will be reflected, because the limits, conditions will change some types of selection procedure will be modified and so on.
So do you consider the approval of this law to be more of a benefit, or an additional burden on the system of bureaucracy?
I think this law is definitely a step in the right direction and I hope it will be confirmed.
The problem that can arise here is that the rules will become &quot;tighter&quot; and it will not be possible to follow them.
Already under the operation of the previous rules, controlled persons are bound by the provider (for example, in the case of regional operational programs by the regional council) to the fact that any non-compliance with the Public Procurement Act means a breach of budgetary discipline.
So is it worth tightening the law in this way?
I think not in this way.
The system must exclude those who want to challenge and abuse it, and not punish those who commit formal misconduct that has no impact on decision-making.
Such a system will only create more pressure on the bureaucracy.
And how to get out of it?
Let&#39;s show where the road does not lead.
Recently, the Prime Minister said that the ODS will not bother entrepreneurs with inspections of the so-called &quot;blackmail system&quot; - and what does that mean?
Is the black system disabled or enabled?
After all, the law must be set somehow, and if it prohibits something, then even the Prime Minister cannot prevent the activity of the office, which has the duty to check and enforce obligations.
He can say, &quot;We&#39;re going to change the law and allow it,&quot; but he can&#39;t say we&#39;re going to act like nothing happened.
There are fairly strict rules in the Public Procurement Act as to what is to be formally done - which is correct in order to protect public competition.
But on the other hand, it is tragic when the applicant with the best offer is excluded only because of formal deficiencies.
The law will never be perfect, but its application must be correct - that&#39;s what I think we lack.
