The group The Tap Tap, together with other performers, also sang a so-called anthem against the end of the world, which is called &quot;End of the World Canceled&quot;.
She is already very popular on YouTube today, will she also perform at these benefit concerts?
Of course, and at the very end, that is, if we succeed in everything and the end of the world does not happen...
It is sung simultaneously by all performers at all three concerts.
The anthems will also be linked together in a unique live broadcast on Czech television.
He wrote the words to this song and Tomáš Hanák plays the main role of Jesus in the clip, Xindl X also sings in it...
How did you come to work with them?
We also cooperate with other personalities of the Czech cultural scene, given that we organize a lot of benefit events and concerts...
We try to intensively involve them in these projects.
It turned out that most of them are interested and enjoy working with us.
What will the proceeds from the concerts against the end of the world go to?
For the equipment of the barrier-free educational center Studeo, which we have been realizing for the sixth year with the civic association Tap at the Jedliček Institute.
Lecturers regularly visit the students of the Jedlička Institute schools and engage them in activities that interest and amuse them.
The students themselves don&#39;t have the means to hire tutors on their own, so we try to make it possible for them in this way.
As part of the completion of the Jedlička Institute, a separate building will be created in the future, to which we will move with this project.
Several musical groups and performers will perform at each concert.
How did you choose them?
We tried to put together a program that will appeal to all generations, including children.
For example, Chinaski, Support Lesbiens, Illustratosphere with Dan Bárta, The Tap Tap, Marián Bango and Jiří Suchý will perform in Prague.
You can find out all the details at www.kpks.cz.
Are you planning any similar &quot;bombastic events&quot; in the future?
In May, we will perform for the first time at the Prague Spring, so we will definitely prepare an interesting program with interesting guests here as well.
Next year we would also like to play at the Czech National House in New York, and personally, when we are in the USA, I would like to connect it with a performance in Washington and Chicago.
Your foreign plans are not minimalist, you have already performed in Madrid, Brussels, London or Moscow, for example.
However, The Tap Tap is a group made up of disabled people.
How do you manage these trips logistically and organizationally?
It is not as terrible as it seems at first glance.
We have five members on an electric cart, their carts have to travel in the luggage compartment, and of course we haul a lot of cargo and tool boxes...
However, so far it has always been done without any problems, ČSA and British Airways were excellently prepared for us, that I was surprised how many times.
Even in Moscow, from which we returned recently, it was without problems.
Thanks to trips abroad, you can compare how each country differs in accessibility, public access to the disabled, and the like.
What have you encountered so far?
After Madrid, Luxembourg, London and other places where everything works better than here, it was in Russia that we witnessed that everything is still in its infancy in the East.
Compared to Prague, Moscow is very barrier-free, here it is still unusual for a person to move alone in the city center on an electric wheelchair.
Even the obvious things, such as giving priority to wheelchair users in the elevator, do not apply there.
Fortunately, civic associations are already being formed there as well, which try to draw attention to the problems of people with disabilities.
And in what ways do we still have to catch up with more developed countries?
There are a lot of things we are still behind on...
But it is important to mention that the improvement and improvement of the situation always depends on the efforts of the people concerned.
In London and Madrid, it is completely normal that even people with a severe handicap can move independently in public, they can go to the toilet, to the museum, anywhere...
However, it is not very common that a large number of people with disabilities actively participate in social life there, on the contrary, we and The Tap Tap are a little ahead!
Respecting the public or accessibility is one thing, but only when we become important athletes, artists, actors, politicians or lawyers, things really start to change.
So far, these are rare cases of people who have a strong will.
The band The Tap Tap is currently very popular, but let&#39;s go back a few years, what made you start it in 1998?
I joined the Jedlička Institute as an educator, where I was surrounded by many young people who were interested in doing something.
And since I&#39;m a musician myself, I play the saxophone, among other things, so I founded a hobby music club together with a colleague.
Well, over time, as our moderator Láďa Angelovič says, it got a little out of hand (laughs).
But the popularity came only in recent years, or am I wrong?
It&#39;s true that it helped us when we started connecting with famous singers and also actively working to promote the band.
We realized that work that cannot be seen is essentially as if it did not exist.
Thanks to contributions from the European Union, we can also afford quality lecturers, equipment and so on.
Was it your goal to take The Tap Tap this high?
From the beginning, I felt the potential to do something different.
Show business is full of things where one imitates the other.
It is logical in a way, everything new is accepted with caution and it takes a long time.
There are very few things that are unique, but I daresay Tap Tap is one of them.
The first impression of a person who sees us for the first time is of course regret, that&#39;s natural...
But that pity is completely unnecessary, because people with disabilities are not suffering all abandoned beings that we have to pity.
They are people who can live a full life and develop, provided of course that they have the necessary means to do so.
I say that when people with disabilities succeed in something, it is not only a shift for them, but for the whole society.
Has being a strict boss, as many people have described you, also contributed to this success?
If we want to do quality work, we have to be uncompromising in many things and require a certain discipline.
But I think that&#39;s completely normal.
Some people come to us with a romantic idea and with their head in the clouds, and when they find out that they have to go to rehearsals twice a week, attend rehearsals and spend a lot of time traveling to concerts, the enthusiasm quickly leaves them.
But this is how it works everywhere, in every group that wants to work and that wants to achieve something.
Currently, the band The Tap Tap has twenty members.
How many of them were there when it started in 1998?
Only one Laďa Angelovič.
We are an open group, people come and go, you can&#39;t help it.
Anyone who has the will and desire always has an open door with us
