Poland and the cosmos.
Last week, at the meeting of the ministers of the countries of the European Space Agency, Poland was accepted as the twentieth member of this European Space Agency, as the second country from the countries of the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of the ESA on November 12, 2008).
Poland started close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and over the following years participated in a number of the agency&#39;s projects.
However, Poland&#39;s journey into space began much earlier.
Polish enthusiasts were already involved in spaceflight before the Second World War; but they were not always met with understanding.
I will remind you, for example, of A. Šternfeld&#39;s lecture at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory, who on December 6, 1933 presented ideas from his pioneering work Introduction to Cosmonautics.
The thoughts of the young engineer (b. 1905) left listeners cold, and years later Šternfeld recalled that only dr. Jan Gadomski was interested in his work.
In 1934, Šternfeld received the Robert Esnault-Pelterie and André Louis Hirsch prize for his Entry into Cosmonautics in France.
The aforementioned Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899 - 1966) later became a great promoter of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and wrote a number of books devoted to these scientific disciplines.
Gadomski became a world-renowned promoter of space travel, and his contribution was recognized by the fact that one of the craters on the far side of the Moon was named after him.
Already in 1925, a railway sink was built in Poland, which was to be equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of the proposal is unknown and the details of the project are not known either.
It is not even clear whether the rocket was to be used to start the dredsin or to brake it.
Information about this dressing is known only from the contemporary press.
Since 1933, the Polish artillery began to deal with rocket missiles.
The research was carried out by the Chamber of Arms Technicians in cooperation with prof. Mieczyslaw Wolfek and prof. by Gustav Mokrzyckiegi.
It is clear from the preserved materials that the research has reached the stage of practical tests.
However, the research was interrupted by the arrival of German troops.
In 1937, a proposal for a photoelectric fighter rocket, designed by the engineer Rohoziński, appeared in the professional press, and in the following year, the work Rakieta - torpeda powietrzna i rakitebomba lotnicza by Leliwa-Krzywoblocký was published.
Both projects were intended for military use of rocket engines.
Just before the war, the Temporary Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy) was devoted to all projects of military use of rocket technology, which coordinated all work.
The committee was founded in 1937, but after two years of activity, its activities were terminated by the start of the war.
Other works devoted to cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war thanks to the work of the Polish Astronautical Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The company is first mentioned in the November 1954 edition of the magazine Problems, in which there are four more extensive articles devoted to astronautics.
In one of them, from prof. M. Subotowicz, it is proposed to create a company that will deal with cosmonautics.
At that time, artificial satellite projects were already underway and it was clear that space research was a promising field.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (PTA) has been trying to join the International Astronautical Federation (founded in 1951), and already in the fall, the PTA became a full member.
And the following year, the first chairman of the PTA, Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902 - 1959), became the vice-chairman of the International Astronautical Federation.
He held this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, PTA has been significantly involved in the development of the highly successful RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) meteorological rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to carry out scientific research.
The first RM-1 type was completed in 1957 and the first launch took place on October 10, 1958.
The rocket with a range of 1800 meters was about 80 cm long and its weight was less than 5 kg.
Later, an improved version of the RM-1A was built, and in the summer of 1959, flight tests of the RM-2 two-stage rocket began in the Bledovská Desert.
The rocket was 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kg.
The next development type was already supposed to be capable of real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket was supposed to have a range of up to 14.5 km and its task was to monitor high-altitude winds.
However, further development was suspended in 1962.
The Meteor-1 rocket developed between 1962 and 1965 became the successor of the first RM-type rockets.
The rocket was designed as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm and the launch weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C) were developed, which differed in the size of the space for scientific instruments.
A space of 0.4 liters, Meteor-1B of 0.34 liters and Meteor-1C of 0.62 liters was available in the rocket Meteor-1A.
The maximum range for all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, development of the Meteor-2 rocket took place at the Aviation Institute, the first flight tests of which began in October 1970.
The Meteor-2 rocket had a launch weight of 380 kg and was capable of carrying a payload of 10 kg to an altitude of around 60 km.
The Meteor-2H and Meteor-3 versions were subsequently built.
Poland&#39;s entry into COSPAR (Committee for Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of a national COSPAR committee two years later should also be mentioned.
Poland also participated in space research on Soviet artificial satellites as part of the Interkosmos program, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslaw Hermaszewski became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remko.
Repealing the Public Works Act is not the answer.
Last week, the Constitutional Court annulled the Public Works Act.
The resolution sparked a lively public debate.
It will certainly be interesting to look at the issue from a broader perspective.
Liberally oriented economic systems in the EU as well as in the globalized world are based on the principle of more, unregulated economic competition.
In its effect, this means that individual economic entities, national economic systems, are in permanent conflict with each other.
The reason is the principle of free trade and the free, unrestricted movement of private capital together with unbridled financial speculation.
As a result of significant differences in the price of labor (wages), there is a price tension.
By this term, it is necessary to understand the situation where the manufacturer tries to survive the economic competition by importing cheap goods by &quot;undercutting&quot; the competitor&#39;s price in order to capture a larger share of the market and thereby increase their own profits.
On a mass scale, this means for most entrepreneurs either to transfer production abroad, or to buy there cheaply, or to disappear. The result is high unemployment in countries where labor prices are high compared to other economies.
Since private capital has no social responsibility and thus responsibility for the unemployment produced by it, the social expenditures of the state necessarily increase.
The whole situation is exacerbated by the complete reluctance of the businessmen to pay taxes and thereby compensate for the economic and social damage caused to society as a whole in the pursuit of profit.
The situation is so widely known that there is no need to provide specific statistical data.
The reckless practices of private capital create a situation in individual economies where the governments of individual countries are forced to enter into mutual competition with the aim of artificially lowering the social level of their own population in order to attract foreign capital to the country.
In other words, governments give their own population to private capital regardless of social decline.
This is manifested primarily in changes to applicable laws.
The goal is to economically force the own population to accept the price dictates of private capital, especially in the area of wages.
This happens on the one hand through a system of economic coercion in the case of long-term unemployment, and on the other hand by limiting the rights of employees in the area of labor law.
The result is growing poverty along with a widening gap between the rich and the poor.
In Germany, there have been public food pantries for many years for the poor who cannot support themselves through their own work.
The number of these people is already in the millions.
As part of increasing the competitiveness of the German economy, it is quite common for cases where properly employed people receive such a wage that the state has to pay them up to the subsistence minimum.
Such a scandal was also published in the case of auxiliary employees of the Federal Assembly.
The austerity measures of practically all southern EU countries undoubtedly lead to the same situation, when people are forced to either emigrate, as was the case in the 19th century, or live on starvation wages at the fringes of society, under the pressure of a catastrophic drop in the social level, in the hope that one day private investment capital will come.
But here it is necessary to ask where does it come from?
If it is from other EU countries, then poverty will move from one country to another, or it will not come at all, because a Chinese, an Indian, a Brazilian, or a Turk, a Moroccan, or an Egyptian, or an African still work for a fraction of a European wage.
This applies to all of Latin America.
Liberal theory and the media claim ad nauseum that the state cannot capitalize on its own economy, that a controlled economy leads to economic disaster.
Private capital fiercely insists on the position that the state must not intervene in the economy through management interventions.
Then one must ask whether private capital does not influence, and now actually controls, politics and thus the entire state in its own egoistic sense.
The answer here is a definite yes.
The proof is the existence of a practically omnipotent and omnipresent lobby in all states.
The result is a desperate situation manifested in the field of corruption, giving mutual benefits, legislation where practically everything is punishable, but nothing is criminal.
In Germany, the situation is such that the state ministries, due to a lack of funds, outsource the drafting of draft laws to private law firms that are closely linked to industry.
These bills are then approved in the Bundestag.
In this way, all power does not come from the people, as Western-style constitutions proclaim, but from financially powerful groups preferring their own interests.
