Movie Argo: Calling Hollywood when it&#39;s worst
In November 1979, a mob of protesting Islamist students overran the US embassy in Tehran and took 52 diplomats hostage.
They were supposed to be released in exchange for the deposed shah Mohamed Réza Pahlavi, who fled to the USA after the revolution, which had been the patron of his regime for several decades.
For the American administration, the situation did not offer a positive way out - it could not afford to throw the Shah overboard, as it would fundamentally jeopardize the trust of allies in other countries.
But she was unable to achieve the release of the hostages in Iran, where the revolution resulted in the establishment of a theocratic regime.
It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later deepened by the fiasco of the attempt to free the hostages by force.
The jailed diplomats were finally released after 444 days, after negotiations were brokered by the Algerian government.
Their fate caused a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment at home.
The debacle in Iran contributed significantly to Jimmy Carter&#39;s loss to Ronald Reagan in the 1980 presidential election.
The movie Argo, directed by actor Ben Affleck, describes one episode of that history that brought America a small victory.
Just before the occupation of the embassy, six employees fled.
After complicated vicissitudes, they ended up in the residence of the Canadian ambassador.
The CIA, in cooperation with the Canadian authorities, managed to get them out of Iran, with the help of an extravagant cover story - they went on Canadian passports as members of a film crew that was inspecting locations in the country for the filming of a sci-fi blockbuster.
A combination of genres
The plan, devised by &quot;exfiltration&quot; expert Tony Mendez, also required the cooperation of Hollywood.
To make the legend believable, the film project was written about in specialized magazines, press conferences were held, the fictitious production company had a real office.
The details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film is based on the memories of Tony Mendez.
Affleck&#39;s film is a strange combination of multiple genres.
On the one hand, a realistically conceived political thriller, at the same time a so-called &quot;caper movie&quot;, the story of a successful stunt, a failure - an example can be the series of Danny&#39;s partners.
The film thus alternates moods - on the one hand, the documentary sequences from Tehran (in the title sequence, iconic period photographs of the events are shown as well as the way in which the same situations were presented in the film - there are no big differences).
On the other hand, light-hearted passages from Hollywood, treated with irony and slight exaggeration.
And then there are scenes from the CIA headquarters and other institutions - men in suits discuss the situation at the meeting tables, in the corridors of the office, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has managed to reboot his career in a remarkable way.
From a mocked actor, he became a respected director and his acting ceased to be the target of ironic remarks.
Argo is his third feature film, following the dark crime thriller Gone Baby Gone (2007) and the thriller The City (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck&#39;s first film that does not take place in the director&#39;s home Boston.
At the same time, the feeling for the atmosphere of the place was one of the characteristics that raised the director&#39;s older films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck also shows it in Argo, where Tehran is &quot;played&quot; by Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, while reconstructing real events - the opening sequence of the fall of the embassy is impressive in its clarity, which at the same time conveys the emotion of confusion and unpredictability that occurs when history moves somewhere out of the blue.
Affleck and his collaborators achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (a fake crew in a Tehran bazaar).
Too many plots in too many places
The director also had to deal with the fact that the story told does not really offer much in the cinematic sense of exciting scenes.
He almost works with it quite successfully, sometimes he comes up with something to match reality - things don&#39;t work out so elegantly there anymore (the scene in which the impending crisis at the Tehran airport is averted by a phone call in America and the chase down the runway seems rather far-fetched).
But Argo&#39;s weakness is the distraction resulting from the need to show too much action in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman are very charming in the roles of Hollywood collaborators, but their characters deserve more space and they are far from the only ones in the film.
Affleck&#39;s film loses a bit of its dramatic thrust, it is a film that can be watched with mild interest, to appreciate the execution and the retro style evoking the thrillers of the 70s.
But it&#39;s hard to pull off.
As a reminder of a still-in-a-way living history and a proof of how exaggerated the notions of omnipotent and omniscient secret services are, it will suffice.
