&quot;People can nominate other incredible ideas from the EU workshop until the end of this year.
The voting itself will then take place until the end of February 2013,&quot; informed Nacher.
Controversial EU regulations include, for example, the compulsory mixing of bio-components into fuel, which as a result harms nature, the ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers only because they contain a relatively small amount of a dangerous substance, or the directive on the size of hen cages, which made eggs significantly more expensive this year .
The de facto ban on the use of the term spread butter or the removal of classic light bulbs from sale also faced criticism earlier.
Quality bananas should be 14 centimeters
The EU apparatus often makes decisions under the pressure of one or another business or industrial lobby, whose demands are usually defended in Brussels by a state or a group of states (so the Czech Republic is now enforcing the demands of its banks even with the threat of a veto).
The interests of the lobby were also behind the fact that, for example, bananas of the highest quality had to reach a length of at least 14 cm in the Union and were not allowed to show &quot;anomalous curvature&quot;.
At the same time, the European Commission defended itself by only harmonizing the existing inconsistent national standards, which complicated trading.
The EU has already softened the standards regarding fruit and vegetables, despite the opposition of some states, pointing out that the existing directives lead to food waste.
Last year&#39;s EU regulation may also be a candidate for victory in the poll, according to which inflatable balloons sold must have a warning that children under 8 years of age must not blow them up without adult supervision.
The EU referred here to American research, according to which balloons among toys are the leading cause of death for children from suffocation.
Similar restrictions now apply to children under the age of 14 when blowing fairground puffs.
Curious ideas are also born at home
The rule regarding the European officials themselves is also rather absurd - everyone who has an official position in the EU cannot use the name Macedonia due to the sensitivity of the topic for Greece and must instead speak of FYROM (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
The server Bankovnípoplatky.com, in cooperation with the association of liberal economists Laissez Faire, nominated for the poll, in addition to some of the above-mentioned absurdities, for example, the EU regulation on the volume of food stocks in the territory of a member state.
The EU established the maximum volumes of food stocks that could be located on the territory of the Czech Republic on the day of our entry into the Union.
The Czech Republic then exceeded, for example, the set volumes for canned mushrooms, for which it was threatened with a heavy fine.
The organizers of the survey were also interested in the idea of paying some countries for not having a sea, and the idea of granting subsidies upon application for a subsidy.
However, these ideas did not originate in Brussels, but in Prague.
&quot;We are handicapped by not having the sea.
We will ask the European Union for a refund,&quot; declared the then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslav Palas (ČSSD) in autumn 2004.
As an argument, he stated that a lot of grain was harvested in our country and as a result of the so-called intervention purchases, the state had full warehouses, which he had to export.
According to Palas, the EU should have paid us hundreds of millions of euros for the fact that the Czech Republic is closer to the ports.
In the end, the European Commission came to the aid of the Czech Republic by organizing a tender for the purchase of grain from countries that do not have access to the sea.
Municipalities were offered a subsidy to obtain a subsidy by the Ministry for Regional Development headed by Minister Pavel Němec (US-DEU), specifically they were supposed to write a subsidy application from Brussels.
EU: Bizarre regulations are the exception
Although the regulations easily become a target of criticism in the member states, the EU&#39;s efforts at regulation and at the same time more efficient functioning and development of the entire Union deserve more recognition, according to a number of experts.
According to experts, a more serious problem is, for example, the use of EU subsidies for projects that do not even have a hint of anything to do with deepening European integration, but which were forced by the member states during budget negotiations.
The fact that, like other EU countries, the Czech Republic has to fight in Brussels for the right to a specific label for its traditional products also arouses emotion among the Czechs, and it does not always succeed in this struggle.
After a six-year struggle with the Germans and Austrians, the Czechs won the name Olomouc tvarůžk, but our producers had to rename the domestic rum, whose tradition dates back to the 19th century, to dozemák.
Only products made from cane distillate, and not from sugar beet, can bear the name rum.
In the official list of registered EU products, in the company of world-famous feta and gorgonzola cheeses, marzipan from Lübeck in Germany and Parma ham, for example, Karlovy Vary crackers, Pohořeličky and Třeboň carp and Žatec hops have already found themselves.
Pardubice gingerbread and Hořice tubes can also be proud of the EU trademark.
