MVRDV architects are proof that real adventures don&#39;t just happen in the head - for example Spijkenisse and the recently built Mountain of Books - 2 images
&quot;The building looks cheerful to me, it looks futuristic. Finally, there is something interesting to see again,&quot; says Lisette Verhaig, who is walking around on the side of the road.
Stefan Spermon, an IT technician at a large company nearby, opines: &quot;Sure, the house is nice.&quot;
However, I wonder why we still need a library today.
Everyone has internet, iPads and e-books.
Nobody voluntarily goes to any of these old-style libraries these days, do they?
Spijkenisse, a housing estate very close to Rotterdam with no job opportunities of its own and not even worth a visit, holds a special record.
This municipality with 80,000 inhabitants has the lowest level of education in the whole of the Netherlands.
To solve this stupid situation, a few years ago it was decided to contribute to general education and build seven nicely painted reinforced concrete miniatures of the fictitious bridges that are depicted on euro banknotes.
But the success of the educational offensive was not dizzying.
And so the city councilors realized that there is only one way to become masters of statistics: we must have a library!
Winy Maas of the Rotterdam architecture studio MVRDV, a master of insanely bold bar graphs and builder of humorous, often even cynical structures, took the matter with his usual calmness and appeared at the competition meeting in 2003 with five books under his arm and a grin on his face.
And while the commission was still looking around in amazement and shrugging its shoulders, the cheeky Maas piled his gifts on top of each other according to size and ended his activist-reasoned speech with the words &quot;Dear city council!&quot;
So this is my proposal for the Mountain of Books in Spijkenisse, the so-called Boekenberg!
Nine years later, the mountain was topped for 30 million euros.
It is part of a revitalization project, which also includes an underground parking lot, a supermarket, a post office and several adjacent residential and terraced houses with a total of 50 apartments.
At the beginning of November, the Mountain of Books was awarded the second place &quot;Best Library of NL 2012&quot;.
The project is also nominated for the Dutch National Wood Award 2012.
Small-town greyness, which until now could not offer more than a postmodern pedestrian zone and an extraordinarily ugly town hall, behind whose white facade you would rather expect a dairy, is thanks to this a little bit more contemporary architecture.
Above all, Spijkenisse now has the first public cultural building in the history of its existence.
A long way to the book
First impression: reader eldorado under the cheese hatch.
There is an elevator through the massif of the mountain, but you will discover the true spatial and reading passions only when you conquer the topography on foot.
The glazed interior is bright and clear from all sides, the floor made of burnt wood and elegant street lanterns clearly express the atmosphere of the public square.
The urban environment is perfect.
You see park benches, a dog, and boys and girls playing soccer.
And books, books, books everywhere.
&quot;Normally there are bookshelves along the facade and there is a large dark space in the middle which is mostly uncomfortable and impersonal,&quot; says Winy Maas.
We turned the classic spatial configuration upside down and moved the space for readers from the inside out.
The interior of the Mountain of Books is skilfully used: in the center there are offices, an internet library, a chess club, an ecological center and a home technology center.
The black bookshelves, which are sometimes wall coverings, window sills and stair railings, are a special treat.
The appearance, structure and smell seem alien.
Even sworn architects and civil engineers shake their heads over the unknown building material.
&quot;We wanted to work with recycled materials here,&quot; says Joop Trouborst, project manager at the Spijkenisse municipality, when asked by the Standard magazine.
And so one day we came across a suitable agricultural waste product at a Frisian farm.
Millimeter fleece made of synthetic material has been used as a substrate under the roots in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands for many years.
It is cheap and time efficient.
The thin textile will last one or two seasons and then it is ready to be thrown into the bulky waste.
For the library, the fleece - for the first time in such a quantity - was pressed into boards with a thickness of four centimeters.
Under the action of heat and pressure, the so-called Landbouwplastic (KLP) turns into a dark, homogeneous and heavy-duty material that smells a bit like a new car and a bit like sports shoes.
