Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most serious sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia and gonorrhea.
Common viral STIs are HIV, human papillomaviruses, genital herpes or hepatitis.
Ringworm and scabies belong to parasitic STIs.
Who belongs to the most affected group?
Syphilis and gonorrhea occur mainly in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute assumes that at least four out of five of all syphilis cases reported in Germany are transmitted through sexual contact between men.
In heterosexual adults, sexually transmitted diseases that occur frequently are chlamydial infections, trichomonads, candidiasis (yeast), gonorrhea, and human papillomavirus.
HIV is relatively rare among heterosexual adults in our country, but roughly 20 percent of people newly infected with HIV belong to this group.
Among adolescents, chlamydia infections occur significantly more often than in other population groups.
According to European surveys, three quarters of all infections concern young people aged 15 to 25.
Moreover, human papillomaviruses are often found among teenagers in our country.
How did the number of infections develop?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases must be reported.
According to the Robert Koch Institute, the number of people infected with syphilis more than doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of people newly infected with HIV has been decreasing since 2007.
In 2011, there were approximately 2,700 cases.
This is roughly one-tenth less than the year before.
What are the symptoms of an STD?
Infectious diseases can cause ulcers in the genital area, difficulty urinating, discharge, pain in the lower abdomen and blisters or warts.
However, they often do not cause any pain or other symptoms and therefore go unnoticed.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they do not offer 100% protection.
Because the agents of sexually transmitted diseases can also be partially transmitted by infection from impurities and close physical contact.
Therefore, experts recommend regular examinations, especially in the case of frequent changes of sexual partners.
In the case of early diagnosis, it is possible to cure most STIs and prevent later consequences.
