Norwegian rakfisk: The smelliest fish in the world?
Five million people living in Norway enjoy one of the highest living standards not only in Europe but also in the world.
Could the secret of the country&#39;s success be linked to the local appetite for an extraordinarily smelly fish?
Take some overripe cheeses.
Place them in the middle of a pile of dirty and wet soccer gear.
Let it sit for a week.
That&#39;s how you get a sense of the paralyzing smell of rakfisk, one of Norway&#39;s greatest delicacies.
I am in the small town of Fagernes, about three hours from Oslo.
There is snow, a beautiful view - and an omnipresent smell in the air.
Rakfisk is salted trout fermented in water for up to a year - it depends on how much you want the fish to stink.
As it gets darker and colder, Norwegians begin to gather here in Fagernes for a festival dedicated to this, how best to say, most captivating food.
&quot;You eat it raw and then drink it with a glass of aquavit,&quot; says Havard Halvarsen, a local professional firefighter, but also the so-called &quot;Rakfisk general&quot; who is responsible for the festival.
All around us, people are eating small cubes of fish and washing them down with copious amounts of alcohol.
&quot;Some people prefer aquavit to rakfisk,&quot; says Havard.
The drink can overpower the smell.
I&#39;ll try a few pieces.
If the fish can avoid your nose, it&#39;s not so bad - it&#39;s akin to a piece of sushi that&#39;s been on a long bus ride.
Rakfisk is a product of a very different time when there was poverty in Norway, and because there were no refrigerators yet, the fish was soaked in airtight barrels of water and salt in the fall.
Then in the middle of winter, when they were well fermented, they were pulled out and eaten - senses dulled by the alcohol, no doubt.
Just a generation ago, thousands of Norwegians were forced to leave their country in search of work, most emigrating to the United States.
Currently, the population is growing rapidly - more than 13% are immigrants attracted by a large amount of work, high earnings and an extensive care system.
Residents of Sweden, an old rival that until recently was much richer than Norway, are flocking to the country for work.
Rakfisk is seen as something important, an indispensable, if rather smelly, part of Norway&#39;s past.
It is among the more expensive dishes on the market.
Everything is expensive though - a small glass of beer or a sandwich will set you back £9 ($14) each.
Norway doesn&#39;t often make the global news - and most residents seem to be fine with that.
The name of Anders Breivik, the right-wing racist extremist who shot dead 77 men, women and children last year, is still mentioned here with distaste.
Instead, the shooting is being called &quot;the July 22 incident.&quot;
Norwegians can hardly believe that in their peaceful country one of their own was capable of such brutality and murder.
Behind Norway&#39;s current wealth lies the growth of one of the world&#39;s largest oil and gas industries from the early 1970s.
&quot;But oil is not the only reason why we are doing so well,&quot; says our waitress Anna, who with her long blond hair and surprisingly blue eyes represents the prototype of Nordic prosperity, as she serves plates of rakfisk.
We are, as you say, sensible people.
Her English, like the English of most people here, is absolutely flawless.
We don&#39;t show off, we don&#39;t like ostentation.
Norway handles its oil wealth very carefully - apart from a small percentage, most of the money from the industry is invested in a special fund intended for future generations.
When everyone else was blowing money they didn&#39;t have in the years leading up to the global financial crash, the Norwegians had their purse strings tight.
&quot;As long as we can ski in the winter and go on trips in the summer, we&#39;re happy,&quot; says Anna.
&quot;And eat rakfisk,&quot; he adds with a carefree laugh.
I&#39;m standing in the snow in line for something to eat - I&#39;ve had enough of rakfisk.
Such a moose burger is definitely something different and is beautifully juicy.
But in the evening, the smelly fish is here again.
The hotel I live in is one of the many places that serve rakfisk for dinner and where the guests choose the best, or rather the most demanding fish for the sense of smell.
They have a connection to the live TV broadcast, in which the presenter in a bow tie is surrounded by plates of rakfisk.
It&#39;s like the Eurovision song contest.
&quot;What&#39;s your score for the best fish up there in the mountains, Thor-Juergen?&quot;
“Here&#39;s our scoring, Havard.
There is applause and laughter.
A man falls from his chair, possibly incapacitated by aquavit.
Or maybe fumes from all that fish.
