Bradley Manning did not complain of mistreatment, military prosecutor claims
Military prosecutor seeks to refute Bradley Manning&#39;s claims of abuse in custody.
The hearing focuses on Manning&#39;s time in military custody in Quantico, Virginia.
The defense wants the case dismissed based on Manning&#39;s rough treatment in prison.
A soldier is accused of stealing thousands of secret documents.
A military prosecutor is trying to prove that Private Bradley Manning, who is accused of the largest leak of classified material in US history, missed numerous opportunities to complain about the rough treatment he allegedly suffered in military custody.
Military prosecutor maj. Ashden Fein cross-examines Private Manning at a preliminary hearing at Ft. Maede argued in Maryland that records of weekly visits Manning had with unit officers during his nine months in custody in Quantico, Va., show no complaints of mistreatment.
The cross-examination, which took place during a hearing on the defense&#39;s motion to dismiss the case against Manning on the grounds of custodial abuse, a punishment in itself, came a day after Manning testified that he had considered suicide while in custody .
An Army intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents while serving in Iraq.
The material was then published online on WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has never confirmed that Manning was the source of its information.
At Friday&#39;s hearing, military prosecutor Fein went over with Manning the forms officers filled out after meeting with Manning at Quantico Detention Center, where he was held in maximum security from July 2010 to April 2011.
The officers asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When asked by Fein about the forms on Friday, Manning admitted that he rated the treatment by his guards as &quot;excellent&quot; and the overall treatment at the facility as &quot;very professional.&quot;
The forms show no complaints of mistreatment, even though officers asked Manning directly about the manner in which he was being treated, Fein argued.
Manning responded that he had verbally expressed concerns regarding various issues and that the officers who visited him had discussed those concerns with him and indicated they would address them, but had not noted the issues.
&quot;They wrote down &#39;no issues&#39; (after discussing the concerns), and that didn&#39;t necessarily mean I didn&#39;t bring them up,&quot; Manning said.
Judge Col. Denise Lind also asked Manning why he did not complain about his treatment in January 2011 when he met with the commission to assess the suicidal thoughts he had expressed on a form a few months earlier.
Manning responded that during that meeting, his intention was to get the &quot;injury prevention&quot; regimen down.
The military said it placed him on this restrictive regime (one level below suicidal watch) for his protection and the safety of others.
&quot;I wanted the custodial officers to know that I was fine and that I wanted to get off this injury prevention regimen ... so that I could enjoy an increased quality of life as I saw it,&quot; Manning said.
Manning testified Thursday about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transported to a detention center at the Marine Corps Base in Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said he considered suicide in Kuwait and once passed out due to the heat.
He stated that not being allowed to know what was going to happen to him and what was going on in the world around him was very disheartening.
&quot;My world just collapsed to Arifjan, that cage,&quot; Manning said Thursday.
I thought I was going to die in that cage.
Manning stated that after arriving at Quantico, he spent most days (at least 21 hours, but often more than 23 hours) in a small cell without any company.
Manning said he was only allowed one mattress, a blanket, slippers, some clothes and glasses.
He said he struggled to walk because sleeping or just lying down during the day was against the rules.
Manning stated that he always slept with the light from outside the cell in his eyes.
He stated that if the guards could not see his face when he turned the other way at night, they woke him up and he had to turn back.
Manning&#39;s attorney filed a formal complaint about Private Manning&#39;s treatment in January 2011.
Manning was transferred to the military prison at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas in April 2011.
On Friday, the judge also asked Manning about the allegations he made in Thursday&#39;s deposition that after being forced to sleep naked in his cell at Quantico one night, he was also forced to stand naked in front of guards and fellow inmates during the morning count.
Manning testified that he was not allowed to cover himself with his blanket during the count.
During questioning by a judge on Friday, Manning said he believed his guards ordered him to put down a blanket to cover himself, but admitted he was not ordered to put it down.
On Thursday, Manning testified that he was forced to sleep naked the night before because he tried to show the officer he was not dangerous.
Manning said he told the officer he could use the waistband of his underwear or his slippers to hurt himself, but he didn&#39;t.
Manning testified that his underwear, his slippers and his glasses were removed from his cell that night.
His lawyer hopes the judge will take into account his experience during his imprisonment and that if he is convicted before a military court, which is expected to begin early next year, he will significantly reduce his sentence.
The defense has said it plans to have Manning plead guilty to lesser offenses and to fight the other charges because they are too extreme.
A hearing is scheduled to begin this week, with a military prosecutor expected to defend the detention conditions as justified.
The Pentagon said in a statement that Manning was being held in accordance with regulations governing all arrestees held in maximum security custody.
Charges against Manning include aiding the enemy, unlawfully causing intelligence documents to be published on the Internet, transmitting information relating to national security, and theft of public property or records.
If convicted on all counts, he could be sentenced to life in prison.
