Another round of bloodshed suggests that any such mishap is futile.
Amidst the usual unnecessary conjecture about who started it, many buildings were reduced to rubble, more than 140 Palestinians, mostly civilians, and six Israelis were killed. And for the first time, rockets from Gaza landed near Tel Aviv, the capital of Israel, and in the holy city of Jerusalem.
But while the Israelis and Palestinians seem stuck in their ancient conflict, the Middle East is changing all around them.
The Arab Spring has upended the old order, and Palestinians and Israelis, whether they like it or not, are caught up in the resulting chaos in the region.
Perhaps this will make their fight even bloodier than ever.
However, there are reasons to think it may break their deadly stalemate.
A war that is neither won nor lost.
At first glance, there doesn&#39;t appear to be much reason for optimism at the moment.
Even if the ceasefire struck on November 21 holds, this week&#39;s fighting has strengthened hawks on both sides.
Leaders of Hamas, the Islamic movement that has ruled Gaza since 2007, will claim they forced the Israelis to retreat, even though Gaza has suffered defeat.
Despite killing several Hamas leaders and trapping the 1.7 million residents of Gaza in one of the most miserable and populous corners of the planet, Israel has not succeeded in destroying Hamas.
And indeed, Hamas is gaining influence in the West Bank, another slice of Palestine currently controlled by its arch-rivals Fatah, a more moderate Palestinian faction.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is on their side.
Islamists throughout the Arab world gained more influence, so Hamas gained powerful and wealthy friends.
