Hosni Mubarak, the secular despot who ruled Egypt for 30 years until his fall in 2011, had no time for Hamas.
On the contrary, the Brotherhood is a cousin of Hamas and its leaders are more influenced by public opinion.
In future diplomacy, Hamas may emerge as a player that cannot be excluded even by Israel or America.
On the contrary, Israeli hardliners will come to the opposite conclusions.
In military terminology, Hamas was put back in the crate.
Israel&#39;s Iron Dome anti-missile system proved its worth and many Hamas rockets were destroyed.
Israelis can sleep better - for a while.
In diplomatic terminology, America is as steadfast as ever. Many European countries also blamed Hamas for starting the latest round of violence.
And most importantly - Israel prospered, especially under the leadership of Benjamin Netanyahu, a prime minister who largely ignored the peace process.
Although rockets from Gaza have killed about 30 Israelis since 2004, Israel has been relatively quiet from suicide bombers, thanks in part to the wall that extends into the West Bank, the main part of what might one day be a Palestinian state, and protects Jewish settlements. which are still growing despite their illegality under international law.
Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party allied with an even more radical group led by Avigdor Lieberman at the start of the campaign for the January 22 election, is in a good position.
Why coddle those treacherous Palestinians by giving them their own state?
If they really ruled the West Bank, wouldn&#39;t they be firing rockets like their compatriots did in Gaza?
We&#39;d better keep them behind that wall and hit them when they stick their heads out.
Perhaps the hardliners will win, but the Arab Spring may change their calculations.
Although the Islamists who are gaining power in Egypt and other countries have little love for Israel, their main priority will be to deal with domestic problems.
Israel&#39;s defense spending is higher than that of all four of its Arab neighbors combined.
Starting a new war with a local superpower will hardly help the new Arab governments to heal their economies.
That President Morsi has worked with President Barack Obama to achieve a ceasefire is a good sign and may mark the beginning of something new.
Israelis should also look at the situation from a long-term perspective.
At a time when the rest of the Arab world is becoming more democratic, denying Palestinians the right to self-determination is creating a powder keg that must one day explode in the Israeli-occupied territories - just like the bus that blew up in Tel Aviv last week.
Repression is already weakening democracy in the Jewish state, and demography is making this situation worse as the Arab population grows.
The bloody forays against Gaza every few years to push back Hamas will increasingly take a diplomatic toll.
Both sides need incentives from the outside.
The answer is what reasonable people on both sides proclaim, most of the outside world, and this newspaper: two states, with Israel ceding territory for security reasons.
