Outside Arabs must also push for an accord between Hamas and Fatah.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than an immediate offer of virtual state sovereignty at the UN.
President Obama also has a part to play in bringing Israel to the negotiating table.
In his first term, he neglected to present his own peace plan.
Now, back in the White House, he seems just as reluctant to enter the process.
This is woefully short sighted.
America has a vital interest in a stable Middle East.
This means a peace settlement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Ugly cigarette packaging laws have come into effect in Australia
The unsightly green boxes, which are the same for all tobacco brands, display warnings for smokers and diseased parts of the body.
Australia&#39;s unsightly tobacco and cigarette packaging laws, the first of their kind in the world, came into effect, replacing brand logos and colors with generic olive-green boxes bearing hideous images of diseased body parts and depictions of children and newborns sickened by their parents&#39; smoking.
Apart from the various health warnings and images, mandatory from Saturday, the only difference between the boxes are the brand names, which are printed in the same small font.
This is the strictest tobacco packaging regime in the world.
The Australian federal government says the aim is to discourage young people from smoking by de-appealing the habit.
It relies on studies that show that if people don&#39;t start smoking by age 26, there&#39;s a 99% chance they&#39;ll never start smoking.
&quot;Even with very young children, you can see that they understand the message that the tobacco companies are trying to sell them with their product,&quot; says Federal Health Minister Tanya Plibersek, citing studies that have shown, for example, that children associate the crown in the logo with the idea of to be a princess
While Australia has one of the lowest smoking rates in the world and the changes will have little impact on the profits of multinational companies, other countries are considering introducing similar measures.
The tobacco industry lobbied hard against the introduction of these laws.
Tobacco companies argued that the bill would increase black market trading, leading to cheaper and more accessible cigarettes.
&quot;This legislation will have serious unintended consequences,&quot; says British American Tobacco Australia&#39;s Scott McIntyre.
Counterfeiters from China and Indonesia will bring in many more of these products to be sold on Australian streets.
Another claims that the laws have increased their business.
Sandra Ha of Zico Import Pty Ltd, a small family-owned business, said demand for silicone cigarette wrappers used to cover unsightly boxes had fallen two months ago when British American Tobacco, Britain&#39;s Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost their an appeal of the laws to the Australian High Court, raised from almost zero sales.
Ha said Zico has sold nearly 6,000 units to wholesalers and expects new stock.
It&#39;s a good deal for us.
As a potential snag, experts cite the popularity of social media among the demographic targeted by the plan.
After a series of Australian laws banning television advertising, sponsoring sporting events and requiring most sellers to hide cigarettes from view, tobacco marketing has moved online.
Australia has banned internet advertising by local companies and websites, but cannot restrict foreign websites.
&quot;If you&#39;re a marketer in the tobacco industry and you only have this small space left to promote your products, the online space is an unbeatable place to be,&quot; says Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney. .
Ms Freeman saw an increase in brand ratings on social media sites such as YouTube, Twitter and Facebook by the &quot;average Honza&quot;.
We have to ask, is this just a private citizen who really loves Marlboro cigarettes and went to the trouble of making this video, or is there a marketing company involved?
British American Tobacco Australia says the industry has focused on how it will deal with the new regulations rather than marketing.
The industry has gone so far as to pay Ukraine, Honduras and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new regulations - countries within the World Trade Organization that say trade is unfairly restricted, despite none of the countries doing significant business with Australia.
The SOO decision is expected in mid-2013.
Minister Plibersek says the government has been in talks with other governments that are considering similar packaging laws.
Canada was the first country to introduce mandatory warning photos in 2001.
They have now expanded to over 40 countries including Brazil, Turkey and Ukraine.
The United Kingdom, New Zealand, South Africa and India are considering stricter laws.
Many smokers in Australia are defiant.
Pictures have no effect on me.
I just ignore them.
&quot;You just take out a cigarette and put the pack back in,&quot; says Victor El Hage while buying a pack with a photo of a tumor in his mouth.
Honestly, there is only one reason for me to quit smoking and that is my little daughter.
James Yu, who owns the King of the Pack newsagent in central Sydney, says the uniform boxes make it harder for him to line them up on the shelves.
&quot;It used to take me one hour to unload, now it takes me four hours,&quot; Yu said.
&quot;The government should just ban them completely, then we&#39;d be like, &#39;OK, that&#39;s it, let&#39;s close the shop,&#39;&quot; he said, throwing up his hands.
In a world of constant connection, it&#39;s not so bad to be bored
Last Thanksgiving I unexpectedly spent five hours at the airport when our plane had mechanical problems and we had to wait for another plane to arrive.
So we had a lot of time to think about boredom.
I won&#39;t lie to you.
Waiting half a day at the airport for the next flight is pretty annoying, despite the distraction of books, magazines and iPhone (not to mention the duty-free shops).
But some researchers and child development experts are increasingly coming out in praise of boredom.
They say it&#39;s good for us (and our kids) to be bored sometimes.
It forces the brain to go in interesting directions, which can promote creativity.
And since most of us are constantly connected to a screen these days, we don&#39;t have a chance to enjoy boredom.
So should we encourage boredom?
Yes.
And no.
But I&#39;ll get back to that.
First, like many people, I assumed that boredom was a relatively new phenomenon that occurred with the advent of more free time.
But as Peter Toohey, a professor of Greek and Roman history at Canada&#39;s University of Calgary and author of Boredom: A Lively History (Yale University Press, 2011), says.
&quot;In fact, boredom has a long history,&quot; he said.
A Latin inscription relating to boredom has been found on the walls of Pompeii, dating from the first century AD.
And then there is also the question of how we define boredom.
The problem is that it has been defined and discussed in many different ways, said John D. Eastwood, a professor of psychology at York University in Ontario, Canada.
After reviewing the research literature and presenting the idea to a target group of about 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues defined boredom as the experience of &quot;wanting to do something that would satisfy me, but not being able to&quot;.
Boredom differs from apathy in that a person is not involved in anything, but would like to be.
He says that in apathy there is no urge to do anything.
He says that at the heart of boredom is a &quot;disruption of the attention process, associated with a bad mood and a sense of time passing slowly.&quot;
Boredom can look a lot like depression.
But Professor Eastwood said that while they may be related, bored people tend to see the problem as the environment or the world, while people who are depressed see the problem in themselves.
Sometimes we think we&#39;re bored when we&#39;re just having trouble concentrating.
In their study, &quot;The Unengaged Mind: Defining Boredom in Terms of Attention,&quot; published in September in the journal Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues pointed to an earlier experiment in which participants listened to a tape of a person reading an article from magazine.
Some groups heard a loud and unrelated television program in the next room, others heard it so quietly they barely noticed it, while a third group didn&#39;t hear it at all.
Those who listened to the TV program in silence reported more boredom than the other two groups - they had trouble concentrating but weren&#39;t sure why and attributed the trouble to boredom.
When you&#39;re trying to focus on a difficult or engaging task, distractions can lead to boredom, said Mark J. Fenske, a professor of neuroscience at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the study&#39;s authors.
On the other hand, when you&#39;re doing something boring, &quot;like looking for bad parts on a factory line, distracting music can help keep you from getting bored.&quot;
In fact, he said, we now know that doodling and doodling, often viewed as signs of boredom, can actually help fight boredom and keep people physically more attentive.
&quot;Research shows that children who are allowed to move around learn more and retain more information than those who are forced to sit still,&quot; Professor Fenske said.
We&#39;ve all experienced boredom at one point or another - my flight being delayed, a blaring speaker, a particularly long movie.
But some individuals are more likely to get bored than others.
To help measure boredom, scientists developed the Boredom Proneness Scale in the 1980s.
The scale includes questions such as: &quot;Many of the things I have to do are repetitive and monotonous,&quot; and &quot;I have so many interests that I don&#39;t have time to do them all.&quot;.
Using these scales, the researchers found that boys tend to be bored more often than girls, said Stephen Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when it comes to the need to have more and different external stimulation.
However, teenagers are generally apathetic.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of human and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he contacted nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
He found that 32 percent of teens said they were bored at school and doing homework, while 23 percent said they were bored when they weren&#39;t at school.
On the other hand, 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson said he did not know whether the percentage of boredom would be higher or lower now, 21 years later.
But he said he knows that &quot;adolescence is a prime time for boredom,&quot; which is largely due to children and youth not being given much control over what they want to do.
So back to my original question, &quot;Is boredom good for you?&quot;.
As research shows, sometimes not, because in its extreme form it can lead people to take absurd physical risks, gamble or abuse substances as a way to relieve it.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have debated the connection between boredom and creativity, said Professor Vodanovich, who has studied the issue for more than two decades.
&quot;Boredom is the brain&#39;s way of telling you to do something else,&quot; said Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at NYU.
But the brain doesn&#39;t always know the most appropriate thing to do.
If you are bored and use that energy to play guitar and cook, it will make you happy.
However, if you watch TV, it will only make you happy for a while, not long term.
So if your child is bored and you give them an iPad, they won&#39;t be bored anymore, but they won&#39;t learn how to entertain themselves or self-manage, Professor Fenske said.
And &quot;this independent management carries over from one situation to another,&quot; the professor said.
Your child will not only learn how to entertain himself, but will gain more self-control in other areas.
I don&#39;t think we really want to celebrate boredom.
But we shouldn&#39;t be too critical of her either.
Rather, our goal should be to feel comfortable when we are out of reach of the constant hum of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agreed.
&quot;We accuse her of needing to be even more bored, but boredom is a painful, restless desire to be connected to something meaningful,&quot; he said.
What people are really looking for, he said, is a way to relax and enjoy their free time.
&quot;In an environment where we&#39;re constantly overstimulated,&quot; he said, &quot;it&#39;s hard to find ways to entertain ourselves when the noise shuts off.&quot;
There is no handbook in Colorado regarding the new marijuana law
Anthony Orozco, a 19-year-old college student and football player from southeastern Colorado, is facing felony charges for something that will soon be legal statewide -- possession of several grams of marijuana and the pipe he used to smoke it.
Mr. Orozco said he was driving with some friends one day in September in Lamar, on the plains near the Kansas border, when he was pulled over.
After an officer found marijuana in the car, Mr. Orozco was issued a summons for possession of drugs and drug paraphernalia -- petty offenses that carry a $100 fine each -- and a court date.
&quot;They treated us like criminals,&quot; Mr. Orozco said.
But is he a criminal?
In the uncertain weeks following Colorado&#39;s vote to legalize small amounts of recreational marijuana, the answer to hundreds of minor drug cases depends on location rather than law.
Hundreds of misdemeanor marijuana possession cases have already been dropped here and in Washington state, which has passed similar measures.
Police departments have stopped charging adults 21 and older for possession of the small amount that will be legally allowed after the law goes into effect in the coming weeks.
But prosecutors in Colorado&#39;s more conservative districts said they would continue existing marijuana cases and still charge people with possession.
At the same time, several cities from the suburbs of Denver to the mountains west are voting to prevent new, state-licensed marijuana shops from opening in their municipalities.
&quot;This case is moving so quickly that I don&#39;t know what&#39;s going to happen next,&quot; said Daniel J. Oates, the police chief in Aurora, east of Denver.
Regulators in Washington state are also scratching their heads.
And they&#39;re looking for guidance on how to set up a system of licenses for cultivation, production, distribution and sales - all by December 1, 2013.
They say Colorado, for better or worse, is ahead of most states in regulating marijuana, first for medical use and now for recreational use.
&quot;Colorado has a more regulated market, so it will be a good guide,&quot; said Brian E. Smith, a spokesman for the Washington State Liquor Licensing Board.
But as Mr. Smith conceded, no place or system can do more than suggest what might work.
&quot;There is no real precedent to follow,&quot; he said.
Washington&#39;s law, known as I-502, takes effect Dec. 6, which also leaves a one-year vacuum during which the state&#39;s licensing system will not yet exist, but legal possession will.
And there are tricky mechanical questions that must be worked out during that time, such as how to balance the state&#39;s &quot;appropriate access&quot; directive to licensed marijuana with its ban on the sale of cannabis within 1,000 feet of schools, parks, playgrounds or child care centers.
&quot;Nowhere will it be more difficult to locate a licensed cannabis business than in urban areas, particularly in the Seattle metropolitan area,&quot; said Ben Livingston, a spokesman for the Center for Legal Cannabis, a recently formed research group.
On Nov. 21, Aurora Police Chief Oates sent an email to his officers informing them that the city attorney would no longer prosecute any citizen over the age of 21 for possession of a small amount of marijuana and that police would &quot;effective immediately&quot; stop charging people for these crimes.
Chief Oates said police will enforce city laws regulating medical marijuana growers and will continue to prosecute drug traffickers and dealers.
In Weld County in northern Colorado, District Attorney Ken Buck takes a tougher view.
After the vote, he said his office would continue to prosecute marijuana possession cases, mostly as a way to pressure users to seek treatment.
Currently, 119 people face charges for possession of 56 grams or less of marijuana, though many face additional charges.
&quot;Our office is charged with prosecuting criminal offenses that were criminal offenses at the time they occurred,&quot; Mr. Buck said in a statement.
The response was also complicated in places like rural Mesa County, where voters rejected a marijuana initiative.
Police in Grand Junction, the county&#39;s largest city, no longer charge adults with possession of small amounts.
The district attorney, Pete Hautzinger, supports the decision, but also decided not to dismiss all pending possession cases.
&quot;I don&#39;t think I&#39;m wasting my time continuing to enforce the law until it changes,&quot; he said.
Although 55 percent of Colorado voters supported the measure, bringing recreational marijuana into the arms of government and the legal system was never going to be easy.
And the mixed reactions across the state have revealed deep divisions among local officials over this grand state green experiment.
For district attorneys, that&#39;s a &quot;cultural barrier,&quot; said Sean McAllister, a Denver attorney who represents marijuana possession defendants and a local spokesman for the National Organization for Marijuana Law Reform.
&quot;They&#39;ve spent so much of their lives prosecuting people that they still can&#39;t really accept that it&#39;s legal,&quot; he said.
As the first states to treat small amounts of marijuana like alcohol, Colorado and Washington are on track to become national test cases for legalizing the drug.
Advocates and state officials are planning new boundaries for legalized sales while also anxiously awaiting guidance from the federal government, which still plans to make the sale and cultivation of marijuana federal crimes.
Marijuana legalization advocates hope the Justice Department will relent.
Despite several attention-grabbing arrests of medical marijuana sellers and patients who use it, the federal government has mostly kept medical marijuana shops open in Colorado, Washington and 16 other states.
While drug agents likely won&#39;t be kicking down doors to seize a small bag of the drug, they are likely to balk at allowing state-regulated recreational marijuana businesses allowed by the new laws, said Kevin A. Sabet, a former drug policy adviser to President Obama&#39;s administration.
Several Colorado cities are not waiting for action from federal authorities.
Even before Election Day, some local governments approved moratoriums on any new marijuana stores, though it will be about a year before any stores can open.
Last week, the western city of Montrose proposed a six-month ban, which is likely to go into effect next week.
&quot;We don&#39;t want to be in a situation where we issue a license to someone and then have a big federal issue out of it,&quot; said Bob Nicholson, a city council member.
Our community voted against this amendment.
We look at what the community voted for versus what the state voted for.
There are really many questions.
Petronella Wyatt: &quot;I was forced to leave Oxford because I am a Conservative.&quot;
Today&#39;s university students are not the only ones being attacked for their views.
I don&#39;t remember ever dreaming of studying at Oxford University.
Both my father and my older brother studied at a university that I thought was the world&#39;s greatest seat of knowledge, a modern wrapped Greek symposium motivating the two pillars of civilization, free thought and tolerance.
And yet, in the late 1980s, within two weeks of entering Worcester College, where I wanted to study history, I packed my bags and plunged into the first scandal of my life.
My father broke down and cried.
My friends were confused.
The Evening Standard claimed I gave it up because I objected to making love to the students in the next room.
Writer AN Wilson famously declared that I left because I was forced to drink from battered mugs.
The truth was less comical.
I ran away.
Yes, I ran away because I was subject to systematic bullying and intimidation.
Not because of my somewhat bizarre name or the fact that I came from a private school.
I was persecuted for one reason, and in this cradle of supposed enlightenment it was both bigoted and barbaric: my father, the late Woodrow Wyatt, was a high-ranking adviser to Margaret Thatcher, and I was a member of the Conservative Party.
You may wonder why I&#39;m bringing this up now.
Simply because recent reports suggest that a new generation of right-of-centre students are suffering similar persecution.
Institutionalized and growing hatred of conservative students at Oxford is so great that last week a group of these students demanded the same protection of equal rights as gays, disabled people and ethnic minorities.
Conservative members of the Junior Year Association (JCR) at Corpus Christi College say they are &quot;often actively isolated, subjected to personal attacks and made to feel unwelcome&quot; because of their political views.
They are calling for the creation of a position on the university&#39;s equal opportunities committee, which would ensure that they can express their views freely.
Their situation was not helped by the recent BBC Two documentary Wonderland: Young, Bright and on the Right about student politics, which portrayed Tories as freaks and neo-Nazis.
The program featured alumnus Joe Cooke, former president of the Oxford University Conservative Association (OUCA), who drove a Rolls-Royce, was dressed in a silver suit and carried a silver-headed cane.
At other universities, conservative students say they are being treated as &quot;scapegoats&quot; because of the introduction of higher tuition fees.
Luke Black, 20, vice-president of the Nottingham University Conservative Association, told Sunday&#39;s newspaper that &quot;left-wing influence in universities is growing.
People think we&#39;re like the Bullingdon Club without ever meeting us.&quot;
Corpus Christi history student Samuel Roberts, 21, who is behind the movement for more protection, says such a climate is &quot;unpleasant&quot;, while OUCA president-elect Stephanie Cherill, 19, says there has been a deterioration in JCR members&#39; attitudes towards people on the right of centre.
&quot;This poses a threat to the atmosphere of intellectual discussion as well as the well-being of members,&quot; he says.
During my first few weeks at Oxford I was in the minority of one member.
I joined in September 1986, 18 years old and cripplingly shy.
Hatred of the Conservative Party was most fervent.
A year earlier, the university had voted to deny former student Margaret Thatcher an honorary degree because of cuts to higher education funding.
The atmosphere would make even Stalinists tremble with fear.
During the first few days of induction week, when new students socialize with each other and with professors, I got a taste of the wormwood to come.
I discovered that not only do professors tacitly condone the poking of conservative students, but they even participate in it with gusto.
The politics of the miners&#39; strike, privatization and government resistance to sanctions against apartheid South Africa were brought to the wood-paneled auditoriums.
My first lecture was on the translation of an 18th century French text into English, and I was not prepared for what followed.
&quot;Miss Wyatt,&quot; said Professor Harry Pitt (now deceased), &quot;please translate the first paragraph.&quot;
It was pretty stiff for me.
Professor Pitt, a little man with a face like cake batter, was very bilious.
&quot;Do the Thatchers refuse to learn French or are they just plain stupid?&quot; he asked.
The other students snickered.
Tears welled up in my eyes.
&quot;I suggest you take some basic French lessons in your spare time, that is, if you&#39;re not too busy with social affairs,&quot; growled Professor Pitt.
Devastated, I returned to my room.
I was sitting alone during dinner at school when I felt a light tap on my shoulder.
It was a second year student named James who introduced himself as an OUCA member.
&quot;I know who you are,&quot; he said kindly.
Unfortunately, it is.
Anyone suspected of conservatism is a target.
It&#39;s bad enough for me, but they know your father is close to Margaret Thatcher, so it&#39;s going to be even worse for you.
Most Conservative freshmen pretend to be Labour.
Later, at the local pub, I made a cowardly attempt to pretend.
I insisted that I disagreed with everything Thatcher said.
This ploy proved unsuccessful.
A first-year philosophy, politics and economics student who (what an irony) went to Eton said: &quot;You are the daughter of a fascist pig.&quot;
You are infected.
The other students took notes with him.
I was perverted, dirty.
&quot;How Do Conservatives Love Each Other?&quot; asked one.
They beat each other up, right?
I felt the way homosexuals must have felt before the liberal legislation of the 1960s.
Could I ever lead a normal life in Oxford?
Would I be forced to hang out with like-minded people only after dark?
Would I have to turn Labor and suppress my natural inclinations?
Three years unfolded before me as a purgatory of ignorance and isolation.
The only openly conservative professor was Norman Stone, a professor of modern history who was based on my faculty.
He was hated not only for being a Conservative, but also for being Margaret Thatcher&#39;s foreign policy adviser and one of her speech writers.
He was almost not there.
He hated the place for its provincialism and pettiness, and for its leanings towards a Marxist-deterministic view of history.
In 1997, he became a professor at Bilkent University in Ankara, Turkey.
&quot;You won&#39;t be happy here,&quot; he told me.
I began commuting from Oxford to my parents&#39; house in London, seeking refuge with my dispassionate metropolitan friends and family.
I told my father that I hated Oxford and why.
He couldn&#39;t believe it.
During his studies at Oxford in the 1940s, all political views were accepted.
&quot;But it&#39;s the best place in the world,&quot; he said pathetically.
They wouldn&#39;t do that, not in the city of dreamy moods.
Even my communist friends always had perfect manners.
His moist eyes darkened.
Try again.
I&#39;m sure it&#39;s just a joke.
It would break my heart if you left.
Exhausted by frequent trips to London, my emotional resilience was deteriorating.
A friend of mine, also a supporter of the Conservative Party, succumbed to the pressure and renounced his convictions.
The following week during class, when another history professor declared in all seriousness that I was an &quot;enemy of the people,&quot; I decided to do the same.
Even though I was blushing inside with shame, I admitted that I was &quot;brainwashed by my parents&quot; and called them &quot;old fools&quot;.
The relief was only short-lived.
My father drove the nail in the coffin of my Oxford career.
At the time, he wrote two columns each week for Murdoch&#39;s newspaper.
My door was locked.
I cowered inside and after five minutes my pursuers gave up.
When they left, I packed my suitcase and caught the first train to London.
I never came back.
You can call me a snooty wimp.
But no 18-year-old girl or boy should be subject to such intimidation and vitriol in an educational institution.
But even more tragically, it was Oxford that not only produced 14 Tory prime ministers, but also hides to this day behind an undeserved reputation as a place of equality and freedom of thought.
&quot;Valentino prefers elegance to fame&quot;
ABC spoke to Naty Abascal, Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisz and other famous clients of the Italian designer on the occasion of the &quot;Valentino: master of fashion&quot; exhibition, which opened this week in London.
