This exhibition is the conclusion of a story in which &quot;il signore&quot; Garavani is the only protagonist, but which could not have been written without his esteemed clients.
Valentino always felt enchanted by the rare and distant world of the aristocracy.
The first hall of the exhibition, which runs until March 3, is bursting with private correspondence and photographs signed by the most important nobles, from Princess Salima Aga Khan to Princess Marie-Chantal of Greece and Margaret of England to Lord Snowdon.
Valentino exhibits these personal memories as trophies of his social rise: from a simple tailor from the town of Voghera in the north of Italy to the idol of the international &quot;bohemian cream&quot;.
There&#39;s nothing wrong with liking royalty.
&quot;At least they don&#39;t stick a starling cigarette in your great carpet, like some wonderful pop-music celebrities do,&quot; says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemiszová.
We both lived in the Alps in the 1960s and 1970s and were good friends.
Valentino is an impressive host and entertains guests lavishly and with elegance.
&quot;We were all very pleased when we were invited to his cottage in Gstaad,&quot; explains the ex-wife of &quot;Heini&quot; Thyssen and a close friend of forgotten beauties like Marella Agnelli or Eugenie Niarchos.
&quot;Valentino always preferred elegance to fame.
And he&#39;s still a star.&quot;
Valeria Mazzová performs Valentino
Even the Argentinian model Valeria Mazzová does not forget the designer&#39;s charisma.
&quot;It&#39;s been many years since we went to his place for dinner after a show in Piazza di Spagna in Rome.
There were twenty of us and among us were Sharon Stone and John Kennedy Jr.
In every detail of his apartment, decoration, food, music, his spirit was reflected and felt in everything.
Thanks to him, all the invitees could feel important and loved,&quot; recalls the top model, who started working with him during Paris Haute Couture Week in 1995.
&quot;He will never go out of style because his designs are works of art,&quot; he concludes.
A show of nobility
Gravani&#39;s life is not a story of obsessions, but of truly requited loves.
He loves people with good breeding and better titles and they love him.
One of Somerset House&#39;s galleries has been converted into a distinctive seventy-metre-long arcade that offers role-reversal: the visitor turns into a model and marches through the arcade to observe a dream &quot;audience&quot; wearing Valentino&#39;s masterpieces as the dress chosen by Jackie Kennedy for her wedding to Aristotle Onassis, the costume worn by Monica Vitti in &quot;Night&quot; or the wool and fur coat that belonged to Empress Farah Diba.
Names such as Sibilla of Luxembourg, Gloria of Thurn and Taxis, Mette-Marit of Norway, Rosario of Bulgaria and Sophie of Habsburg shine in the audience of mannequins.
Naty Abascal and the designer in 2006
Many of these clients say that the first Valentino is like a first love, &quot;you can&#39;t forget him&quot;.
&quot;I remember it perfectly.
They were trousers, a shirt, a &quot;gillette&quot; vest and a jacket from the autumn-winter collection of 1971-1972.
It was a gift he made for me,&quot; says Naty Abascalová, one of the designer&#39;s muses.
&quot;I prefer him to others because of his femininity and his great love for women, because he underlines our beauty,&quot; adds the former Duchess of Feria.
&quot;I really like the colors she uses, they really brighten and give a &#39;sparkle&#39; to the face.
The proportions are perfect.&quot;
Even princess and fashion icon Patricia della Giovampaola d&#39;Arenberg can&#39;t forget how she first dressed Valentino.
Growing up and living in Italy, she longed to come of age and have the opportunity to wear one of his evening gowns...
It finally arrived in the late 1990s.
&quot;I bought my first Valentino dress for a celebration at the castle of my cousin, Prince Edouard de Ligne.
It was a red dress that had a ruffled skirt, a ruffled bodice, and a strapless top.
It was a dream come true,&quot; says Rodrigo d&#39;Arenberg&#39;s widow.
&quot;Valentino is lax about fashion, his passion is timeless,&quot; explains the Italian aristocrat, whose life unfolds between Paris, New York and Buenos Aires.
Princess d&#39;Arenberg has stored the designer&#39;s formal dress &quot;very carefully... because a dress is not just a dress, it&#39;s also a set of memories that they have inside&quot;.
&quot;King&quot; of fashion
The highlight of the exhibition at Somerset House is Marie-Chantal Miller&#39;s wedding dress from her wedding to Pavel Grýký in 1995.
It took four months of work and 25 &quot;girls&quot; (as the designer calls his seamstresses) to create this ivory-colored silk dress with sewn-in pearls, twelve different types of lace, and a four-and-a-half-meter train.
According to the journalist Suzy Menkes, the greatest authority in the specialized press, these dresses represent a landmark of high fashion at the end of the 20th century, &quot;the return of high society clients&quot;.
Valentino, dazzled over the years by an elitist &quot;savoir-être&quot;, is now its best example.
As Cavaliere di Gran Croce (Italy&#39;s highest decoration), Cavaliere del Lavoro, Commandeur de L&#39;Ordre des Arts et des Lettres and decorated with the Legion of Honor, Garavani amasses as many honors as any of the husbands of his clients.
&quot;My attention was always attracted by his elegance, calmness, well-groomed and perfect appearance,&quot; admits the Princess d&#39;Arenberg.
&quot;The last time I saw him was a month ago at a gala dinner at the Orsay Museum.
He was at table with Countess Jacqueline de Ribes, a great friend of mine.
He was flawless, time had not left a mark on him.&quot;
When the princess says it...
The hardest craft in the world: sulfur carriers in the Kawah Ijen volcano region
For four euros, porters in the Indonesian volcano region gamble with their lives and health as they carry 70 kilos of sulfur down steep stone paths.
There are people for whom their work is hell, and there are those who literally work in hell.
Such is the case of Ant Wijayi, one of 400 miners who make a living extracting sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano in the east of the Indonesian island of Java.
Because of this, he has to work his way down to the bottom of the crater every day, where sulfurous gases escape from the interior of the Earth and turn into a solid state when it comes into contact with air.
After cutting large blocks of sulfur, which together weigh up to 70 kilos, he carries them on his shoulders in two bamboo baskets along steep stone paths.
It is only 250 meters to the top of the volcano, which rises 2,386 meters, but it takes over 40 minutes for the exhausted porters to climb up at a turtle&#39;s pace as they keep their balance and carefully consider their steps to avoid slipping and plunging into the abyss.
They know that any stumble could cost them their lives, as happened to one French tourist who fell off the rocks of Kawah Ijen years ago.
Miners at Kawah Ijen earn five cents for every kilo of sulfur they mine
Once at the top, they make their way past tourists who photograph them as if they were monkeys in a circus, and wearily carry the heavy baskets to a scale the mining company has placed a little lower, at 1,850 meters above sea level.
This is PT Candi Ngrimbi, which has mined the volcano since 1960 and has never paid its workers more than 662 Indonesian rupiah (five cents) per kilo of sulphur.
He then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 cents) to the petrochemical industry, as the mineral has a place in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even to bleach sugar.
&quot;Because it normally carries 70 kilos, we earn about 46,000 rupees (3.8 euros) for each trip,&quot; explains Anto, who usually makes three trips a day.
One trip takes him three hours and he is broke at the end, but he can earn 138,000 rupees (11.5 euros) a day.
While this seems like a pittance for such an inhumane effort, it is three times what he would have earned in the field.
&quot;The daily wages of miners here are very high. For example, picking coffee is paid 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) per day and the salary for a fortnight is two million rupees (167 euros),&quot; explains a porter who used to work on a tourist island Bali as a bricklayer.
There his salary was 75,000 rupiah (6.2 euros) a day and the work was not that hard, but Anto returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a village near the volcano, for a serious reason that is as compelling as sulfur in Indonesia: &quot;He married I am with a young girl from Bali who is Hindu and I have taken her to Java to convert to Islam.&quot;
Anto has asthma, his breathing is difficult, he is constantly coughing and his eyes are irritated by toxic gases
At the age of 27, Anto risks his life three times a day in the Kawah Ijen volcano, whose sulfur has already begun to take its toll on him, even though his face is protected by a special mask and glasses.
He has asthma, his breathing is bad, he is constantly coughing and his eyes are irritated by the toxic gases escaping from the volcano.
That&#39;s the price he has to pay to achieve his dream.
&quot;I will work for two more years because I want to open a shop or study Spanish or French,&quot; he promises in more than passable English.
This likable and intelligent young man, struck down by fate, could be a tour guide, a waiter or a hotel receptionist, but instead he works as a porter.
He shares a dirty wooden shack with other porters and gets up at two in the morning every day because the sulfur keeps bubbling up at night and its characteristic yellow color turns blue and glows in the dark.
Despite the surrounding darkness, Anto walks into the crater and lights his way with a small flashlight that he has attached to his helmet and bought with his own money.
About 400 bearers carry baskets with sulfur from the bottom of the crater on their shoulders
Although the company has high revenues, it has not mechanized the mining of sulfur to save costs, nor does it provide any equipment to porters working on their own and with such efforts.
In fact, they don&#39;t even get a share of the 30,000 rupees (2.5 euros) photography fee that, along with the 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) entrance fee, the park rangers collect from tourists who come to photograph the volcano and its human inhabitants mules.
&quot;This work is for the cattle, not the people,&quot; counters Madrusin, a burly 42-year-old porter who has been working at Kawah Ijen for three decades, ever since he left school.
He can lift up to 110 kilos and assures us that he will keep working &quot;as long as possible&quot; because he needs the money to pay for the education of his three sons, aged between 18 and 10.
I will not retire, I will die here, because the volcano has been my whole life
Although the sulfur burns the throat and stings the eyes when the wind suddenly shifts and traps the miners in the thick fumes that rise from the volcano, the miners are so tough that none of them complain of suffering from serious illnesses... but it is evident from of their frequent respiratory problems, arthritis, knee pain and shoulder wounds caused by the weight of the baskets.
Unainik, who balances his basket on his back, can only carry 50 kilos at the age of 53.
Each day, he and his colleagues mine 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which are then transported by three trucks up a steep path through the thicket to a warehouse in Tamansari, 18 kilometers away.
&quot;I&#39;m not going to retire, I&#39;m going to die here because the volcano has been my whole life,&quot; Unainik declares, opening his mouth wide with several teeth missing.
Of his five sons, the eldest, 30 years old, also makes a living by mining sulphur.
Time passes, but the constant misery of one of the hardest trades in the world persists from generation to generation - the trades carried out by human mules in Kawah Iljen.
Singapore is looking for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame not having children on career, stress and the cost of living and education.
&quot;Singapore&#39;s population needs to grow.&quot;
I am married and I am a patriot, you are my wife and you are a patriot. Let&#39;s fulfill our civic duty and give birth to a new life!
It may seem unbelievable that this slogan is part of an advertisement for menthol candies, but despite it - or perhaps because of it - the video went viral on YouTube earlier this year in Singapore.
The lines are part of a rap that uses local innuendos such as &quot;put the bun in the oven&quot; to mock Singapore&#39;s birth rate.
Advertising agency BBH, which created the video, hopes that with this ad they will be able to draw attention to the problem in a humorous way.
The agency&#39;s artistic director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the influence of music to make people do &quot;their civic duty&quot;.
“This is strictly an internet thing, so it had to be fun and funny.
It is the biggest problem of this country.
We are the worst in the world at reproducing our population, so we felt it was a topic we needed to touch on.
We knew that the government was trying a lot of things like spreading pheromone perfumes or organizing dating parties.
Many of these ideas may have been creative, but not entirely functional.
So we thought why not do the most creative thing possible, like compose a rap, to solve this problem.&quot;
1.2 children
One who doesn&#39;t take this very lightly is the Singaporean government.
It spends $1,300 a year to encourage citizens to have more children.
The government&#39;s Marriage and Family Package provides up to $15,000 per child, extends maternity leave and provides cash benefits.
But all these measures had little effect.
Singapore is a wealthy, high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for the conservatism of its leaders and strict social controls.
The birth rate in Singapore, taking into account the stratification of the population, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time the birth rate exceeded 2, which is considered the recovery rate, was in 1976.
Why don&#39;t Singaporeans have more children anyway?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the National Population Bureau&#39;s Marriage and Family Department, says this is because of &quot;better education&quot; and &quot;a wider range of career opportunities&quot;.
&quot;So people have a wider range of options when it comes to life goals and priorities, it&#39;s not just marriage and family,&quot; he explains.
These changes in social norms contributed to an increase in the number of single people and to the delay of marriage and childbearing. The result is a decrease in Singapore&#39;s birth rate.
While there have been efforts within immigration policy to drastically increase the influx of immigrants as a countermeasure to population decline, this has created resentment among local residents.
Some Singaporean websites show undisguised xenophobia against many new immigrants, especially the Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and making little effort to integrate.
The increase in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why last year Singapore&#39;s ruling party recorded its worst election result since independence.
After the election, there was an effort to solve the problem using quotas and higher fees for foreign workers.
Unexpected consequences
While declining birth rates have known effects on national economic growth, tax revenue, health spending and immigration policy, there have also been some unintended consequences in the case of Singapore.
The government is trying not to build so many small houses.
For example, it began to influence the real estate business.
The Urban Development Authority has begun regulating the number of small apartments known as &quot;shoe boxes&quot; that can be built in certain urban zones.
These apartments have an area of 46 square meters and have been very successful in sales.
However, there are concerns that these flats may promote a youth lifestyle and discourage developers from building large family homes.
But Lim Yew Soon, managing director of development firm EL Developers, says their &quot;shoe boxes&quot; are selling far faster than larger houses.
“They are more popular, selling days to weeks faster than larger homes.
That&#39;s why they&#39;re so much better for our cash flow.&quot;
However, he admits that the new standards set clearer rules for developers who were previously limited when they wanted to offer too many small houses in one project.
Too stressed
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules could aim to boost the nation&#39;s birth rate, speaking to Singaporeans working in the downtown financial district suggests they won&#39;t have much of an effect.
&quot;People are always stressed, houses are expensive, as is education, so many people put it off,&quot; says the young official.
&quot;Let the others have children.
But for me it&#39;s important to rely on my own money and time,&quot; says another young man in his twenties.
Both men and women cite careers, stress, and the cost of living and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So no matter how hard the government tries to force citizens to have children, it is still Singaporeans who have the final say on starting a family.
What is private offline is also private online
Privacy.
According to the dictionary published by the Royal Spanish Academy, it is something of a personal nature or &quot;an area of private life that everyone has the right to protect against any intrusion&quot;.
What is privacy for a person under the age of 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and on social media?
Does he understand the dangers to which he is exposed when he publishes matters on the Internet that he would certainly not tell anyone in normal communication?
Journalists from elPeriódico interviewed five boys and girls between the ages of 10 and 15 who are frequent Internet users.
In four cases, they considered the concept of privacy as &quot;something completely personal&quot; on a personal level and as &quot;username and password&quot; when it came to social networks.
&quot;I wouldn&#39;t share my biggest secret,&quot; says 10-year-old Jorge, trying to explain the importance of privacy on places like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he&#39;s had accounts for two years.
&quot;They are top secret secrets, my mom may know about them, but not the whole world,&quot; she claims.
&quot;On FB I post nice photos or photos of us playing.
I also chat with friends there.
I wouldn&#39;t share a photo that wasn&#39;t mine or a photo that would make fun of someone,&quot; he says.
This boy understands that it is wrong to post obscene photos, photos of naked people or photos of crimes, or write degrading or rude comments.
Jorge says he knows all 35 friends he has on FB and his nine followers on Twitter.
Most are relatives.
Among them is the mother, who has the name and password of one of the accounts.
&quot;I started a Twitter account to express my opinions and write interesting posts.
I don&#39;t know if anyone will answer me, I just put them there,&quot; he adds.
&quot;Social networks are fun, I can talk to relatives who are far away or quickly communicate with friends,&quot; he says.
He says without hesitation that he would never accept a request from a stranger.
He wouldn&#39;t even care if someone recommended him to someone he didn&#39;t know.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
This teenager has accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and on the last mentioned network he admits that he does not know 20 people on his friends list.
&quot;I&#39;m not afraid of it because we have something in common, like music,&quot; he says.
According to this boy, none of them asked him for anything, nor did they ask for his address or phone number.
&quot;If they pressured me or required me to, I would simply remove them from my account,&quot; he admits.
José signed up to Ask after reading a recommendation on Twitter.
This boy is no stranger to what is now called cyberbullying.
&quot;They blackmailed a friend&#39;s acquaintance on the social network.
They threatened him and demanded money.
He never found out who it was,&quot; he confirms.
According to José, the victim did not log out of the account.
&quot;She just activated private mode.&quot;
It then explains a series of steps to set up your account securely.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would post photos of acquaintances in unpleasant or embarrassing situations.
&quot;Of course I would do it if someone bothered me or if I just wanted to.
Even though I know it&#39;s cyberbullying,&quot; she claims.
Key questions
Marielos Porrasová, English teacher and graduate of Education and Teaching, believes that in order for children and teenagers to navigate social networks correctly, they must understand that the main goal of these networks is to inform.
He states that: &quot;The Internet originated as a means of finding information, but when social networks appeared, the rules of the game changed.&quot;
Marrielos Porras notes that academic Marc Prensky, a Yale graduate in education and author of the article Digital Natives and Digital Immigrants, introduced these terms to explain the phenomenon.
&quot;Digital natives are children and young people who were born in the age of this technology.
We are digital immigrants who have to teach them, while we are still learning ourselves,&quot; he says.
He explains that it is a complex topic &quot;because we are asking them to discern what is appropriate to spread, publish and say, and what is not, at an age when they are not yet mature&quot;.
Also, to be - as far as the environment is concerned - prudent, at a time when what they most desire is to be popular, have thousands of friends and not think about the consequences&quot;, he adds.
According to this specialist, the most effective way to show children and teenagers what privacy is is to ask questions that make them think.
&quot;Telling them not to do something doesn&#39;t work,&quot; he adds.
Furthermore, Marrielos Porrasová lists some of the possibilities: There are things you wouldn&#39;t tell a stranger, so why do you do it on the Internet?
Or: Would you like it if someone posted your photo the way you posted a friend&#39;s photo?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you tag people in party photos, have you asked for their permission?
And one more thing: Does everyone need to know what you&#39;re doing all the time?
Another point is for them to realize that they have to behave in the Internet environment the same as outside it.
It&#39;s the same rules.
&quot;A person is guided by respect, morality and other principles outside the Internet, and it should be the same on social networks,&quot; he claims.
Surveillance
Estuardo Guardia, a university professor, primary school teacher and educational consultant, explains that it is essential that parents of children carefully read the rules of social networks.
&quot;If they understand the intricacies of each, they have a good basis for talking to children about the consequences of setting up an account online.
For example, in terms of age or what is allowed to be shared or published,&quot; he says.
Guardia believes that it is crucial to remind children of the traditional rule of &quot;don&#39;t talk to strangers&quot;.
The South American Summit ends and the Lima Declaration has not been published
The Sixth Presidential Summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) held in Peru ended today without the issuance of the Lima Declaration that was announced and reportedly signed by the seven presidents present.
The Efe agency repeatedly tried to get access to the document signed at the sixth meeting of heads of state and government of the Unasur organization, but representatives of the Ministry of Foreign Affairs and the Office of the President, who initially stipulated that they would publish the document after the end of the summit, said that it would later be published on the website of the Peruvian government.
They further stated that the content was released by Peruvian President Ollanta Humala in several brief press statements.
Journalists had limited access to information throughout the summit.
During the meeting, a video of the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room without sound, with the message &quot;confidential session, audio disabled&quot;.
The small amount of information available to journalists was provided by the press spokesmen of some of the governments who were present at the meeting, but not by the Peruvian spokesperson.
The only document released during the meeting was a list of participating presidents, which angered hundreds of journalists from various national and international media who demanded more information.
Peru&#39;s presidential office later sent out an email to the media with a &quot;final statement&quot; from the summit, but it is only a statement from President Humala, not the official document that concluded the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the third Summit of South American and Arab Countries (América del Sur-Países Árabes, ASPA), and even on this occasion the originally promised Lima Declaration was not published, despite being eagerly demanded by the press.
On ASPA&#39;s official website, it can be seen that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to ensure the broadcast for all journalists, but completely blocked the flow of information.
The summit ended, among other things, with the joint commitment of Chile and Peru to accept the judgment of the Hague Court of Justice, which resolves the border dispute between the two countries.
Peru&#39;s President Ollanta Humala and Chile&#39;s President Sebastián Piñera met during a regional meeting and confirmed they will respect the decision of the International Court of Justice in The Hague, which will hear arguments from both sides on Monday in the case launched by Lima against Santiago.
&quot;We will submit and execute the judgment that will resolve the dispute that we are discussing today in this international court,&quot; said President Humala together with his Chilean counterpart.
&quot;Chile was, is and will be a country that respects international law, the peaceful resolution of disputes, conventions and international courts,&quot; added Piñera and greeted President Humala with a handshake next to the flags of both countries.
The confirmation by the two presidents that they will abide by the ruling of the International Court of Justice was made public after Colombia this week adopted the Bogota Pact, expressing submission to the judgments of the international court that ruled on the maritime border with Nicaragua, which Colombia considered to be completely wrong.
The summit was held without the participation of the presidents of Brazil (Dilma Rouseff), Venezuela (Hugo Chávez), Bolivia (Evo Morales) and Argentina (Cristina Kirchner).
Paraguay was expelled from Unasur in 2011 after the impeachment of then-president Fernando Lugo and did not attend the meeting.
Host President Ollanta Humala was tasked with opening the morning&#39;s speeches and closing the Lima summit shortly after noon.
The President read the final document, in which he informed that 16 agreements had been adopted and activity was planned on 31 projects between South American countries, with investments amounting to 17 billion dollars.
In addition to the accepted agreements, he mentioned that the member countries of the UNASUR organization will take &quot;important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which residence agreements are being extended.&quot;
He informed that actions are being supported to improve &quot;cooperation in the fight against civil insecurity and international organized crime, for better availability of medicines and cheap internet in all corners of South America and for joint and effective measures against the risks of natural disasters&quot;.
When Europe is in crisis, &quot;(Latin America&#39;s) economic consolidation should not have a victorious essence, but should serve to expand our productivity and show our peoples a better future,&quot; added Humala.
&quot;We have decided to prioritize a group of 31 symbolic projects that will improve transport links in different parts of South America, especially rural and border areas... so that our countries are better connected and create new economic ties,&quot; the Peruvian president said in a speech read.
He mentioned that five of these projects concern Peru and the transverse axes of its territory from the coast to Brazil, and the other two concern better connections with Ecuador, but he did not give more details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
&quot;We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to return it to the Union of South American Nations&quot;, from which it is currently excluded.
Another issue highlighted by the summit was the need for Latin America to continue to be a prosperous and peaceful region that is integrated and has good neighborly relations.
In this sense, Colombian President Juan Manuel Santos said before his participation in the regional meeting that he hopes to meet with his Nicaraguan counterpart Daniel Ortega in Mexico on Saturday to respectfully discuss the judgment of the International Court of Justice regarding the maritime boundary dispute, which is contested by Bogotá.
&quot;It is possible that I will meet with President Daniel Ortega tomorrow (Saturday),&quot; Santos said.
&quot;We will discuss all solutions, none are excluded, not even a treaty with Nicaragua, which would require negotiations with that country,&quot; he emphasized.
&quot;I hope to be able to tell President Ortega to conduct the negotiations in the most civilized and considerate way possible,&quot; Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet in Mexico on Saturday to attend the inauguration of Mexican President Enrique Peña Nieta.
As part of the summit, Union Defense Ministers tentatively met to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which seeks to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the defense of the region.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay are members of UNASUR, although the last-mentioned country is currently excluded.
Peru is the temporary chairman of this regional bloc.
Rafael Correa: South America must learn integration from Europe
Ecuadorian President Rafael Correa announced today that the creation of common citizenship is a goal in which &quot;South America, in this case, really needs to learn from Europe.&quot;
Correa, who was attending the sixth presidential summit of the Union of South American Nations (Unasur) in Lima, told state television TV Perú that Europeans &quot;killed each other in World War II&quot; and in other conflicts, &quot;but now they are practically one homeland.&quot;
In this sense, he defended the project of creating South American citizenship, which the member countries of the Unasur organization support.
&quot;It is necessary to achieve the free movement of citizens and workers within any South American country, which is already happening among the members of the Andean Community, but there are still regressive areas that want to return us to the past,&quot; he pointed out.
Among other things, the Ecuadorian president stated that he agrees to the reorganization of the Organization of American States (OAS) on the condition that the influence of the Anglo-Saxon states is reduced and those who signed the San José Pact on human rights are taken into account.
&quot;Those who are in charge never commit to anything, and we South Americans, on the contrary, will sign everything.
It is incomprehensible that the Inter-American Commission on Human Rights in Washington is funded by the United States,&quot; he said, referring to the political asylum granted by Ecuador to WikiLeaks founder Julian Assange.
President Correa confirmed that he does not regret this decision because he did not betray his principles and respected his &quot;deep democratic values and human rights&quot;.
He added that at the time &quot;there were reasonable suspicions that Assange could be extradited to a third country regardless of the ongoing process&quot;.
In addition, he criticized the Swedish judiciary for asking him to be questioned on Swedish territory for an alleged sexual offence, while &quot;Swedish&#39;s own legislation allows for the questioning to be carried out by video conference call, which could take place from the Ecuadorian embassy in London&quot;.
Correa said there was a risk that Assange&#39;s physical and mental health would deteriorate.
&quot;I have not spoken to him since he has been at our embassy, but the ambassador informed me that he has minor lung problems, but nothing serious,&quot; the Ecuadorian head of state said.
&quot;However, there is a danger that his physical and psychological condition will deteriorate, because he is confined in a small space without the possibility of movement in the fresh air.
This would affect everyone&#39;s health,&quot; he added.
President Correa noted that the solution to the asylum granted to Assange since June at the Ecuadorian embassy in London, based on a permit that allows him to travel to Ecuador, is in the hands of Great Britain, Sweden and the European courts, stressing that talks have taken place with London to resolve the incarceration founder of WikiLeaks.
&quot;We do not negotiate about human rights, we do not use such a word in this case, but there were constant talks.
The solution to this problem is in the hands of Great Britain, Sweden and European courts, because Assange&#39;s lawyer Baltazar Garzón is leading a series of proceedings in various European instances,&quot; he mentioned.
