AIDS victims today are the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 years old when his test result was confirmed: HIV positive.
&quot;It was like a bolt of lightning struck me,&quot; he says, recalling the moment of truth, which the doctor tried to &quot;mitigate a little bit,&quot; but apparently to no avail.
The boy kept it a secret from his family.
He decided to take his illness on his own shoulders and started to learn about it. And with such commitment that he has already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
He is undoubtedly one of the oldest patients of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital of Guadalajara (HCG), where he came in 1994 after several battles with the disease.
Fabrizio has been living with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) since the age of 22, something unimaginable in the early 1990s when there was a lot of doubt, few treatment options and more stigma.
At that time, even the director of the Mexican Institute of Social Security (IMSS) clinic did not say goodbye to him &quot;because he had a cut.&quot;
Back then, having AIDS was synonymous with death.
Now it is possible to survive with this syndrome and live fully.
However, there are many people who do not know about their illness and only come when the virus has destroyed the organism and weakened the immune system, and then they become victims of accidental infections.
31 years since AIDS appeared in the world, or at least since the first documented cases, &quot;it means a great success that the life expectancy of a patient who starts treatment in time and in an appropriate way is exactly the same as that of healthy people&quot;, said Jaime Andrade Villanueva, head of the HIV Unit at the Civil Hospital in Guadalajara, stating that this information was confirmed in April of this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectologist and HIV/AIDS specialist Andrade Villanueva explained that scientists have come to the conclusion that since 2008 AIDS is not a death sentence, but that the length of survival and full life depends on the degree of impairment of the immune system of patients who are diagnosed with the disease, with better those who do not use drugs: people with 200 CD4 cells can live up to 30 years, and people with 500 CD4 cells up to 50 years.
Simply put, this means that someone who is diagnosed with HIV at the age of 25 can, according to these findings, &quot;live up to 75 without problems if they follow the treatment&quot;, the doctor explained in the interview.
To emphasize this progress, it is worth recalling that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
Although the death rate has decreased significantly in recent years and, in the case of Mexico, the number of people who died of AIDS fell from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (Yearbook of the Joint United Nations Program on HIV/AIDS - UNAIDS), it is also true that that since the discovery of AIDS, according to national statistics, 60 percent of patients have died.
In the state of Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011 and 187 by May of this year. However, universal access to antiretrovirals has been ensured since 2005.
- Why do people continue to die from disease?
- &quot;It seems to me that the problem is not in the possibilities of access to treatment.
This is how I see it, this is how it happens in our hospital.
For at least the last 12 years, we have not run out of medicine. The problem is that patients come at a very advanced stage because they do not know the state of the infection, i.e. at a late stage of the disease.&quot;
He adds a compelling figure: &quot;Nine out of ten patients present when some associated infection is already evident. The only thing that needs to be done to make a greater impact on the overall mortality rate is to diagnose the disease earlier, and that&#39;s why testing for the disease needs to be offered on a large scale to all persons who request them&quot;.
In his proposal, he agrees with specialists and officials from the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS in the state of Jalisco, as well as directly with patients like Fabrizio, who came to have tests done in a private laboratory only because his friend did it, and despite his young age he had already developed AIDS and was also suffering from Kaposi&#39;s sarcoma, a cancer that is one of the usual complications.
&quot;Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some think they are going to die and don&#39;t want to know anything else.
&quot;If I&#39;m going to die, I&#39;d rather go out three times a week,&quot; they say, but that&#39;s not my case.
The change was for the better, I eat healthily, I exercise, I take medicine.&quot;
To this day, his parents only know that he suffered from cancer.
&quot;I live a normal life like everyone else.
I work, I have a lot of activities, I travel, I lead an active sex life, but responsibly, I take care of myself and the other person,&quot; enumerates Fabrizio, who accepted the call to share his experience with the MILENIO JALISCO newspaper, so that today, as part of World Day AIDS motivated those who are afraid with his testimony.
&quot;Let them get tested. If they&#39;ve taken a risk, let them know as soon as possible if they&#39;re HIV positive, that&#39;s better. And if they&#39;ve already been diagnosed, let them realize that they can live like anyone else if they&#39;re responsible.&quot;
This message of his summarizes the slogan of the battle against AIDS in this year 2012.
Condoms behind the counter
There is a big gap between health programs and ordinary citizens, said Ricardo Salazar, a Guadalajara-based journalist who investigates HIV.
And the biggest gaps are in prevention.
In the places dedicated to this task, &quot;the distribution of condoms has really increased, before they gave us one or two, today they give us packages of a hundred condoms, which is very good, but there are still people who do not have access to condoms&quot;, he said.
Teenagers are among the most susceptible to new infections.
&quot;What do you want it for?&quot; is a common question full of irony and judgment from social workers, school counselors, pharmacy staff and medical personnel that teens want to avoid, the reporter says.
He proposed to change this ineffective division. Let condoms not only be behind the counters, but let the hundred of them be found in dispensers in public toilets, in places where young people often go.
&quot;It&#39;s not an endorsement of promiscuity.
Nor is it a question of &quot;paying them beer and a motel,&quot; as Governor Emilio González responded when asked if he would agree to distribute condoms in his district.
There is no such sexuality. It is best to make condoms available to those who are already having sex,&quot; he noted.
Key numbers in the state of Jalisco
13,435 cases were recorded (12,158 AIDS cases and 1,317 HIV cases).
This state ranks fourth in Mexico in new and established AIDS cases and 13th in HIV.
92% of the infection takes place through sexual contact, 6% through blood and 2% perinatally.
It is estimated that about 50,000 people may be living with the HIV virus, as for every registered case there are four to five people who do not know about the disease.
The ruling upheld by the United States Court of Appeals, which does not recognize Grupo Vitro&#39;s bankruptcy debt restructuring in Mexico, sets an unfortunate precedent for any national business with branches in a neighboring country and a solvency problem.
Thus, the corporate restructuring procedures allowed under Mexican law do not appear to apply in the land of the stars and stripes, despite international agreements.
The approval of the judgment issued last June 15 by Judge Harlin Hale in the bankruptcy court for North Texas effectively leaves Mexican companies defenseless against the possibility of confiscation of their assets on the other side of the El Bravo River.
However, the ruling opens the door for the major Mexican glass maker to appeal to the United States Supreme Court on three irregularities.
At the outset, while the judge in this case says creditors should follow United States bankruptcy law, the New Orleans-based Fifth Circuit Court of Appeals says bankruptcy proceedings in Mexico are the main procedure.
Firstly, it would indicate ignorance of international procedural cooperation in cases of insolvency of multinational companies.
In essence, the United Nations Model Law for the Unification of International Trade Law was created for this purpose, which appoints the American Law Institute as the arbitrator.
Second, the judgment states that without the vote of the branches from the internal corporate structure, where the indebtedness of the parent company Vitro to the branches is recognized, the required majority to approve the restructuring would not have been achieved.
However, Mexican law allows this option.
The fact is that the Vitro case was not the first in which this scheme was adopted.
There are half a dozen examples, such as Agremex and Comercial Mexicana, whose intra-corporate debts were guaranteed by the Federal Bankruptcy Institute.
In addition, it is true that even after deducting the votes of the branches, the creditors - who were against Vitro in court in the United States, i.e. &quot;vulture&quot; funds such as Aurelios Capital, Aurelios Convergencia, Elliot Internacional and Liverpool Limited - would not have achieved a majority.
They would get about 45 percent to 37 in the vote.
This information is not taken into account by the Court of Appeal.
From another point of view, the court blames Vitro for the difficult situation it has faced since 2008 - against the background of the severe economic crisis that hit the United States.
In the meantime, González Sada&#39;s family business will file an appeal for a new assessment directly at the Court of Appeal, so that the assessment will take place with a full participation, i.e. with the participation of five judges, since only three originally voted.
If he fails here, he will seek a review of the process by a higher court, in this case the United States Supreme Court, as a remedy.
What is significant about the case is that the court omitted a document submitted by the Mexican government as an amicus curiae detailing Vitro&#39;s procedure under the Bankruptcy Code and pointing out that the company made it easy for itself by going along with the agreements signed by both countries to confront the law with Chapter 15 of the United States Bankruptcy Code.
In addition, it is pointed out that the country has submitted to the principles of the United Nations International Trade Commission, i.e. the rules designed for international insolvency cases, which guarantee equality for debtors and creditors.
Impact on both sides: punishment for Vitro and the state.
Overall rating
