Héctor &quot;Hetin&quot; Reyes: &quot;Basketball was my life&quot;
Basketball legend Héctor &quot;Hetin&quot; Reyes has been associated with this indoor sport for more than 60 years and has traveled the world thanks to it.
Few people in Puerto Rico have as many memories of local basketball history as Héctor &quot;Hetin&quot; Reyes.
Before a stroke confined him to a wheelchair in 2008, Reyes was passionate about the sport for more than 60 years, both as a junior player, a player in the BSN National Basketball League, owner and coach of the Vaqueros de Bayamón team in the National Basketball League , or the president of the Puerto Rican Basketball Federation.
&quot;I have held many roles throughout my life in basketball, including several at the same time, such as when I was president of the BSN National League, general manager of the national team and president of the federation in the 1990s,&quot; Reyes recalled when Primera Hora newspaper reporters visited him at his home in Bayamón, where he has lived for more than 50 years with Isabel, his faithful wife.
“Basketball was my life.
Reyes is not exaggerating in his claim.
The walls of his house, which are almost all decorated with photos and memorabilia from his long career, testify to this.
Bayamón in the heart
With the greatest emotion of all, he guards those commemorating his time with los Vaqueros from the mid-1950s, where he was a player until 1982, when he also celebrated 15 years as a co-owner or owner of the team.
&quot;Those were my best years, the ones I enjoyed the most because I had the opportunity to participate in eight championships with Los Vaqueros starting in 1967, either as owner, co-owner or coach.
It was a string of successful years, including five championships held between 1971 and 1975.
And then I said goodbye to one championship - in 1981, when Jerome Mincy debuted in BSN.
That&#39;s when &quot;Cuco&quot; Ortiz took over the team, who was an excellent leader,&quot; Reyes said.
&quot;I remember Gene Bartow, who used to coach here and was at the University of Alabama at Birmingham at the time, said to me, &#39;I&#39;ve got a six-footer for you.
Do you want him?&quot;
And that was the beginning of Mincy, one of the best players Puerto Rico has ever had.
Bartow then referred me to point guard Raymond Gausse, who became a member of the team and one of our top scorers.
I remember him saying that if Mincy brought Bayamon a championship win, Gausse would contribute to the next one.&quot;
Gauss enjoyed the championship when he played for the Los Vaqueros team, but only from a distance, because in 1988 he was already acting as president of the basketball federation.
At that time, he wanted to fully devote himself to his duties and enjoy Mincy&#39;s placement in the national team.
&quot;I remember the first time we beat the United States in an Olympic qualifier in Mexico in 1989.
Then came the 1990 World Championships where we finished fourth, but we should have gotten bronze if it wasn&#39;t for the Canadian referee who made us repeat the final throw-in,&quot; Reyes said.
Is the 1990 World Cup squad the best national team you&#39;ve ever seen?
He is among the best, just like the one who beat the Dream Team in the 2004 Olympics.
But my favorite was the national team at the 1991 Pan American Games in Cuba when we won gold and beat a United States team that was pretty similar to the one that blew us bronze at the World Championships.
That team not only had Mincy, Gausse, Ramon Rivas, Fico López and &quot;Piculín&quot; (Ortiz), but also the youngsters (Javier) &quot;Toñito&quot; Colón and James Carter, the León brothers (Francisco and Edgar) and Mario &quot;Quijote&quot; Morales , who was unable to make the team in 1990 due to a knee injury.
The team that may not have had a perfect composition, but managed to win us a gold medal and bring us great joy, was the team from the 1995 Olympic qualification in Neuquén, Argentina.
With roster players like &quot;Canito&quot; Nieves, Pablo Alicea and junior player Rolando Hourruitiner filling in for players suspended for brawling at the Pan American Games in Mar de Plata, we won gold against all odds.
Who was Puerto Rico&#39;s best player?
That was without a doubt Piculín Ortiz.
His numbers from international tournaments are impressive.
No one from Puerto Rico has achieved results at this level like Piculín.
Not to mention his tenure in the various leagues he played in.
Who was the best Puerto Rican coach?
This is very difficult.
We had a very good generation that includes Julio Toro, Flor Meléndez, Carlos Morales, Raymond Dalmau and Armandito Torres.
Of the young ones, I really like the work of Leo Arillo.
Which of your achievements in the federation do you consider to be the greatest?
That I was part of the most famous era of the national team from 1988 to 1995 and that in the early 1990s the BSN national league had up to 17 teams in one season.
What did you not have time to prove?
There were things I wanted to introduce, like the division of youth categories by region.
For example, that the boys from Ponce would play only in their region and compete with teams from other corners of the island only in the national playoffs.
Now the kids travel a lot and play too many matches, which is not necessary.
I also see the benefit of mandatory certifications and courses for coaches, assistant referees and referees.
It pleases me.
What are you doing now?
I mostly listen to music, watch YouTube videos of music from my time, enjoy my grandchildren and occasionally go to basketball games.
And of course I enjoy the company of my wife Isabel who has always been by my side.
Actor Larry Hagman has died
Larry Hagman, who was born on September 21, 1931 in Forth Worth, Texas, became world famous for his role as John Ross Ewing, better known as &quot;JR&quot; in the television series Dallas, in which he embodied a man who acted recklessly and was malicious and manipulative.
Larry Hagman, whose role as predatory oil tycoon JR Ewing on the TV series Dallas became a symbol of hunger in the 1980s, has died.
He was 81 years old.
Hagman, who returned this year as JR in the new Dallas series, died Friday afternoon of complications from cancer, according to an official family statement provided to The Associated Press by Dallas production company Warner Bros.
&quot;Larry returned to his beloved hometown of Dallas, where he once again played the iconic role he loved most,&quot; his family said.
Larry&#39;s family and closest friends were with him in Dallas for Thanksgiving.
&quot;Linda Gray, who played his wife in the original and new series, was with Hagman at the time of his death in a Dallas hospital,&quot; announced her agent Jeffrey Lane.
He brought joy to everyone he knew.
&quot;He was creative, generous, funny, kind, kind and talented and I will miss him terribly.
He was unique and lived his life to the fullest,&quot; Linda Gray said in the announcement.
Hagman was diagnosed with cirrhosis of the liver in 1992, and he himself admitted that he had been drinking heavily for years.
In 1995, a malignant tumor was found on his liver and Hagman underwent a transplant.
Years before Dallas aired, Hagman made a name for himself on television as a decent guy in the lighthearted comedy I Dream of Jeannie, which aired on NBC from 1965 to 1970.
Here he played the character of Captain Tony Nelson, an astronaut whose life changes when he meets an attractive girl (a genie) played by Barbara Eden and takes her home to live together.
He also starred in two short-lived sitcoms, The Good Life (NBC, 1971-72) and Here We Go Again (ABC, 1973).
His film appearances included roles that were well received by critics: The Group, Harry and Tonto and Primary Colors.
But it was Hangman&#39;s masterful performance as the incredibly repulsive JR that propelled him to stardom.
The CBS drama series about the Ewing clan and other personalities around them aired from April 1978 to May 1991.
The promotional slogan &quot;Who shot Dzhejar?&quot;, which was supposed to raise expectations for a work full of emotions, when Hangman&#39;s character is almost murdered, caused not only a huge number of speculations of viewers around the world, but also risking millions of dollars in bookmakers.
This also helped the episode achieve a viewership record.
The November 1980 episode in which the answer was revealed averaged 41 million television viewers. Dallas thus became the second most-watched entertainment program in history, after the end of the series MASH in 1983, which was watched by 50 million viewers.
JR was shot by his sister-in-law Kristin (played by Mary Crosby).
Kristin got pregnant with JR and he then threatened to call her a prostitute if she didn&#39;t leave town. But there were others who had reason to attack him.
Hagman played Ewing, an insatiably greedy man with a charismatic smile: a scheming businessman and unfaithful husband who tried to get his alcoholic wife Sue Ellen (Linda Gray) locked up in a mental institution.
&quot;I know what I want JR to have on his tombstone,&quot; Hagman said in 1988.
It should read, &quot;Here lies Honorable Citizen JR Ewing.&quot;
This is the only thing that didn&#39;t work out for him.
Victoria Principal, who starred in the original series, remembered Hagman on Friday as someone who was &quot;brilliant on and off screen.&quot;
He is unforgettable and irreplaceable to millions of admirers in the world and in the hearts of all of us who were lucky enough to know and love him.
Ten episodes of the new series of Dallas were broadcast by TNT a few months ago with great success.
&quot;Filming of five episodes of the second season has already been completed and the sixth is currently being filmed,&quot; the TV station reported.
There was no immediate statement from Warner or TNT about how the series would continue after Hangman&#39;s death.
A native of Fort Worth, Texas, he was the son of actress and singer Mary Martin, who starred in such classics as the musicals South Pacific and Peter Pan.
Mary Martin was a very young girl when she gave birth to Larry in 1931, fathered by her lawyer husband Ben Hagman.
In the early 1950s, Larry tried his luck on the stage in New York and then served in the Air Force in England from 1952 to 1956.
There he met the young Swedish designer Maj Axelsson, whom he married.
The married couple had two children, Preston and Heidi, and for a long time they lived in the Californian city of Malibu, where many celebrities stay.
In 2001, he published an autobiographical book, Hello Darlin&#39;: Tall (and Absolutely True) Tales about My Life.
&quot;I didn&#39;t put anything there that I knew could hurt or harm someone,&quot; he told Prensa Asociada at the time.
After a liver transplant, he became involved in the promotion of organ donation and worked as a volunteer in a hospital, where he helped fearful patients.
&quot;I give them advice, I give them courage, I meet them when they go for surgery and after,&quot; he said in 1996.
I try to give them comfort in the sense of &quot;don&#39;t worry, it will be a little uncomfortable for a while, but you will be fine&quot;.
He was also an anti-smoking activist and participated in various campaigns.
A course that explores the &quot;end of the world&quot; begins
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
When religion professor Stuart Charmé decided to do a course on the end of the world this semester, he knew the lure was irresistible: The end of the Mayan calendar&#39;s &quot;long count,&quot; set to come on December 21, was seized upon by many as evidence that the end of the world is coming
Charmé, however, had no idea what was in store for him in the next few months: A catastrophic Hurricane Sandy, a budget impasse that some are calling &quot;debt Armageddon,&quot; and a growing conflict involving Israel, where doomsday Christians say the Apocalypse will begin .
&quot;I didn&#39;t realize this was going to be the most apocalyptic semester ever,&quot; Charmé told students at Rutgers University in Camden, New Jersey, this week.
When you look at what&#39;s going on in the world today, like we have 30 days left, it&#39;s a really good time.
And remember, bad means good to the apocalyptic minded.
And he&#39;s not the only professor offering courses about the &quot;end of the world&quot; this semester, which is theoretically the last in history.
At Temple University, Assistant Professor Barry Vacker teaches a course on &quot;Means, Culture, and the End of the World.&quot;
Each week, students explore apocalyptic topics such as nuclear war, zombies, viruses and bacteria, and global warming.
&quot;We&#39;re looking at why these ideas expand over time,&quot; he says, and how they offer hypothetical scenarios that drive certain human behaviors.
For example, if nuclear material gets into the hands of terrorists, war may break out.
This month, students analyze movies with apocalyptic themes and examine how they differ from real-life examples.
&quot;I tried to inform the students about what is possible, probable, believable and impossible,&quot; Vacker says.
On Pennsylvania State University&#39;s main campus, Latin American history professor Matthew Restall and his colleague Amara Solari, an assistant professor of art history and anthropology, have teamed up to teach a course simply titled The End of the World.
&quot;We&#39;re not adding &#39;2012&#39; because we&#39;re always open to running the course again if the world doesn&#39;t end,&quot; Restall said.
Despite the &quot;imminent doom&quot;, students must study, create projects and take final exams.
At Penn State, the final exam will be held on the eve of the Apocalypse, leaving students with no choice but to work &quot;right up until the evening of the supposed end of the world,&quot; Restall said.
The courses have become quite popular.
&quot;It stretched into two hours,&quot; Restall said of his course for high-grade students, of which 35 have signed up.
Weeks and weeks before the start of the semester, we received emails asking if there was still space.
The students themselves assure that the course is one of the most interesting.
&quot;I find it fascinating to see what people do to comfort themselves,&quot; said Bridgid Robinson, 23, a religion and sociology major from Haddonfield, New Jersey, at Rutgers University in Camden.
And so an apocalyptic, secular or religious mindset is just a matter of consolation or the absence of it.
Will Wekesa, a 25-year-old psychology and nursing student, said he had seen all the apocalypse movies.
&quot;I&#39;ve never heard of a class in which it could be taught before,&quot; he stated.
&quot;I&#39;m enjoying it.&quot;
But no student, let alone professor, interviewed said they believed in a December 21 end date.
&quot;Our first project was about a Mayan prediction, and we&#39;re kind of debunking it,&quot; said Julie Zeglen, a 21-year-old senior at Temple University in West Chester.
&quot;The Mayans never predicted the end of the world; it&#39;s just a key point in the calendar,&quot; Restall said.
But he added that there is an apocalyptic anxiety in Western culture that goes back several centuries, in which people respond to changes in their environment by predicting the end of the world.
The Internet caused this speculation to flourish.
&quot;Elsewhere, people don&#39;t think about it,&quot; he said.
This happens in the vast majority of the English-speaking world.
Joseph Dougherty, a professor of religion at La Salle University who is lecturing in the Philippines this year, was quick to respond when asked if he knew of any &quot;end of the world&quot; courses there.
&quot;The Philippines is not participating in the end of the world,&quot; he wrote, indicating an exception to the high office.
We have grace from the Pope.
Restall noted that there has been talk of many doomsday dates over the years, and said that if nothing happens on December 21st, &quot;people immediately start thinking about the next date&quot; or philosophizing that December 21st is the beginning of a seven-year period at the end of which the world will end.
The date is taken lightly by students and professors alike.
A few said they intended to go to the &quot;end of the world&quot; festivities.
&quot;I&#39;ll probably call a few friends to laugh together,&quot; explained 20-year-old communications student Samira Ford.
